<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier on Financial Crisis in Southeast Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The Asia-Pacific region will
achieve great economic developments in the 21st century and will
play a more important role in international affairs, visiting
Chinese Premier Li Peng said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, Premier Li added, this area will not be the ``sole
center of the world,'' nor can we yet boast of a so-called
"Asia-Pacific century."
</P>
<P>
As a general trend, the world is developing into a multi-polar
planet, in which Europe, America, Latin America and Africa will
also enjoy many of their own achievements, Li said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier's remarks were made in answer to questions
on the financial crisis ailing Southeast Asia during an interview
with Russian TV, the Independent Newspaper and the Interfax news
agency.
</P>
<P>
Despite its impact on the momentum of development in the
affected countries, the financial crisis has not fundamentally
impaired the potential for an economic upturn in this area, Li
said.
</P>
<P>
The affected countries are determined to remedy the defects in
their economic structures and policies, and to strengthen the
market monitoring mechanism as well as implementing precautionary
measures against financial risks, Li said.
</P>
<P>
They have also decided to boost regional economic cooperation
among the countries concerned, Li added.
</P>
<P>
In the long run, the premier envisions an optimistic future of
economic growth for Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
As members of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC),
China and Russia, share a wide range of mutual interests in the
Asia-Pacific area, Li pointed out. He said he hopes the two
countries will make a joint effort to play a positive role in this
area.
</P>
<P>
"We have every reason to believe that China and Russia will
serve as important factors in maintaining the stability and in
boosting the economic development of the Asia-Pacific region in
the new century," Premier Li concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Recommends Better Disposal of Offshore Oil Rigs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission
agreed Wednesday in a recommendation that offshore oil and gas
platforms no longer in use should not end up as waste on sea beds
around Europe.
</P>
<P>
All except a limited few of the 600 such platforms, the
recommendation suggested, should be completely, safely and
economically removed and taken to land for recycling and safe
disposal when no longer in use.
</P>
<P>
The recommendation was made by European commissioners Ritt
Bjerregaard and Christos Papoutsis, who are in charge of
environment and energy affairs respectively.
</P>
<P>
It was also recommended that future rules in this aspect should
be based on the principle of a prohibition of disposal of such
platforms in the sea.
</P>
<P>
The platforms to be exempted from the rule would have to be the
existing large concrete platforms for which there is currently no
proven technology to remove and where the environmental impact of
disposal is limited.
</P>
<P>
It was suggested that existing installations may be exempted in
exceptional cases from the prohibition. But this should only
happen after detailed evaluation and consultation of all parties
concerned.
</P>
<P>
Energy Commissioner Papoutsis said: "We have succeeded in
successfully combining energy policy with environmental
protection.
</P>
<P>
"Sea disposal is neither a realistic nor a desirable option for
the great majority of disused oil and gas installations. By
encouraging on-shore dismantling and recycling, we are not only
helping the environment but also creating jobs in communities
where they are badly needed," he added.
</P>
<P>
In European waters, there are now approximately 600 offshore
oil and gas platforms. Some 100 are the large steel platforms
directly concerned by the recommendation in that they represent 85
percent of the total mass of steel in the North Sea installations.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that in the North Sea alone, about 450 steel
platforms will be taken out of use over the next 20 to 30 years or
15 to 20 platforms a year on average.  
</P>
</TEXT>
