<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Wholesale Trade Up 13 Percent Last Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Wholesale trade in Canada saw
the largest increase in 13 years in 1997, Statistics Canada
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Annual sales by wholesalers reached 287.1 billion dollars
(198.1 billion U.S. dollars) last year, up 13.1 percent from 1996.
</P>
<P>
High demand in both domestic and foreign markets made Canada's
wholesale trade grow considerably in all trade groups in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Wholesalers of farm machinery and equipment reported the
highest increase of 21.8 percent in annual sales last year.
</P>
<P>
Wholesale sales of motor vehicles and parts surged 20.0
percent, while lumber and building materials up 19.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The metals, hardware, plumbing and heating equipment had the
lowest annual increase of 1997, which was 6.4 percent, the agency
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
