<HEADLINE> China, Russia Stress World Multipolarity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Premier Li
Peng said here Wednesday that both China and Russia shared the
idea of Multipolarity in world politics rather than domination of
one or two countries.
</P>
<P>
Li made the remarks in a joint interview by Russian TV, the
Interfax News Agency And Independent Newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The world affairs, he said, should be handled by more
countries, and every country can play its own role in
international affairs.
</P>
<P>
The premier said China will not seek hegemony, and it will
oppose any country which is seeking the hegemony in the
world. Both China and Russia maintained that multipolarity will be
help to world peace and stability, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Li added that as permanent members of the U.N. Security
Council, China and Russia are influential countries in the
world. The two countries, which share common views and stands on
many international and regional issues, are keeping in close
contact and consultation with each other, he said.
</P>
<P>
The premier said amid the rapid development of multipolarity,
it is significant for the two countries to further enhance the
cooperation in international issues.
</P>
<P>
Li said he exchanged views on the Iraqi weapons inspection
crisis with Russian President Boris Yeltsin on Tuesday. Both of
them agreed to make joint efforts to promote the peaceful solution
to the crisis, he added.
</P>
<P>
Li arrived here Tuesday for a two-day official good-will visit
to Russia following his visits to Luxembourg and the Netherlands.
</P>
</TEXT>
