<HEADLINE> Philippine Embassies in Middle East on Full Alert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
placed on "full alert" all its embassies and consular offices in
the Middle East in preparation for possible eruption of war
between the United States and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine News Agency Wednesday quoted Department of
Foreign Affairs officials as saying that all diplomatic offices in
the region have made emergency plans to evacuate promptly the
Filipinos in dangerous zones.
</P>
<P>
The country has about 600,000 workers in the Middle East but
only 50 of them are in Iraq with the Philippine embassy there. The
rest are in neighboring countries including Kuwait, Bahrain, Saudi
Arabia, Qatar, United Arab Emirates, Oman and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Evacuation will involve either bringing the Filipinos back to
the Philippines or just moving them to safer places in the region,
the Philippines News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Iraq-U.S. standoff has not yet shown signs of abating.
United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan will visit Baghdad on
Friday to try to avert a war between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
