<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Investigates Spanish Ferry Firm for State Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission on
Wednesday opened an investigation into state financing made
available to the publicly-owned Spanish ferry company, Transmed.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive body of the 15-nation European
Union, also warned the Spanish authorities that they should
suspend the payment of state aid to the company until commission
examination of the case is concluded.
</P>
<P>
The commission is examining whether the annual budget of 40
million ECU (43 million U.S. dollars) that the Spanish government
forecast as necessary to compensate for the losses incurred on the
services and awarded under the contract is justified.
</P>
<P>
The investigation does not mean that there will be no ferry
services between Spain and surrounding islands.
</P>
<P>
It merely calls into question the amount of subsidy that the
Spanish government is making to Transmed to offset the loss the
company incurs in providing public services.
</P>
<P>
Commission officials said that the commission is bound by the
Maastricht Treaty to open an investigation into the case because
the manner in which the Spanish authorities tendered for this
public service did not comply with European Union rules on state
aid to the maritime sector.
</P>
<P>
Since 1952, Transmed has provided the ferry service between the
Spanish mainland, the Canary Islands, the Balearic Islands, Ceuta
and Melilla on the coast of north Africa.
</P>
<P>
For this, the company receives a state subsidy to cover the
annual deficit incurred in providing ferry service.
</P>
<P>
Under EU state aid rules, direct financial aid designed to
cover operating losses is generally considered a state aid that is
not compatible with the Common Market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Imposes First Merger Regulation Fine on Samsung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission
decided Wednesday to issue a fine -- the first ever -- of 33,000
ECU (35,600 U.S. dollars) against Samsung for breaching merger
regulations.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean company was alleged to have failed to notify
in due time the European Commission of its acquisition and control
of the American company AST Research.
</P>
<P>
Carrying out this operation without the commission's
authorization was an infringement of the merger regulation that
went into effect in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The fine was the first since the regulation went into force.
Commission officials said the relatively small amount of the fine
was based on the fact that the operation had no damaging effect on
market competition.
</P>
<P>
Another reason for the small fine was that Samsung had
eventually notified the commission of the acquisition and the
infringement appeared not to be intentional. The South Korean
company acknowledged the breach and cooperated with the commission
in its investigation.
</P>
<P>
Both Samsung and AST have significant activities in the
European Union in the manufacturing and sale of electronic goods
and personal computers.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive body of the 15-nation union, said
the combined market position of Samsung and AST did not raise any
competition concerns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
