<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Thailand to Strengthen Border Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and Thailand
will intensify joint development efforts along their border in
line with calls to step up regional trade and facilitate
transportation of goods, Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We agreed that various government agencies must play their
parts in facilitating the transportation of perishable and
non-perishable goods crossing the Malaysian-Thai border and also
the Thai border with Laos," Badawi said at a joint news conference
with his Thai counterpart Surin Pitsuwan after their meeting here.
</P>
<P>
Badawi said while trade between Malaysia, Thailand and
Singapore has been increasing, the transportation of goods could
be improved.
</P>
<P>
Recommendations for this purpose would be submitted for further
discussions at meetings of the Malaysia-Thailand Committee
probably in the middle of this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Badawi said Thailand had proposed that the closing time of
check points at the Malaysian-Thai border be extended.
</P>
<P>
"This is also good as we are also encouraging tourism," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Surin said Thailand would like to see Malaysians and Thais
living along the common border benefit from the developments in
the Indonesia-Malaysia-Thailand growth triangle, and to
participate actively in every endeavors undertaken by both
governments.
</P>
<P>
Badawi said during the two-hour meeting, the two sides also
discussed international and regional issues including the tension
between Iraq and the United States.
</P>
<P>
He said Thailand had requested Malaysia to support its
participation as an observer in meetings of the Organization of
Islamic Conference.
</P>
<P>
Surin arrived here Wednesday afternoon for a two-day
familiarization tour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
