<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Producer Prices Drop Sharply in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. prices at the
wholesale level dropped by 0.7 percent in January thanks to a
steep decrease in energy costs, the biggest one-month dip in over
four years, the Labor Department reported here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The department said that its Producer Price Index (PPI), which
measures prices before they reach the consumer, was held down by a
3.7 percent fall in energy prices, the biggest drop since a 5
percent decline in February 1991, the end of the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
While the robust economy has pushed the U.S. unemployment to
the lowest levels since the early 1970s, inflation measured by the
PPI and the more closely watched Consumer Price Index (CPI) has
been well tamed.
</P>
<P>
In a separate report, the Commerce Department reported Wednesday
that construction of new homes and apartments remained at a high
level of an annual rate of 1.54 million units in January.
</P>
<P>
That was down a slight 0.3 percent from the previous month, but
December's performance was revised sharply higher. It was reported
that the construction of new homes and apartments actually rose 1
percent in December instead of previously reported decline of 0.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
For all of 1997, wholesale prices fell 1.2 percent while
consumer prices were up just 1.7 percent. Both were the best
performance since 1986.
</P>
<P>
Many economists believe inflationary pressures will remain
moderate for the whole of this year as the U.S. economy is flooded
with Asian imports which are made cheaper by steep declines in Asian
currencies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
