<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-18 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Says Low Oil Prices "Temporary" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The minister of petroleum of
the United Arab Emirates has said the current weakness in oil
prices was temporary, the official Wam news agency reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The recent price fall was due to the decision by the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) to increase
its output ceiling by 10 percent to 27.5 million barrels a day
starting from January this year, Wam quoted the Minister Obeid bin
Saif al Nasir as saying.
</P>
<P>
It was also because of the economic turmoil in south-eastern
Asia countries and the prevalence of relatively warm weather in
the northern hemisphere, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
"We know through previous experience that prices do not
continue to move in one direction only. They must have their ups
and downs," Nasir said.
</P>
<P>
Nasir, also current OPEC president, said that to shore up the
prices, the crucial issue was that all member states should not
exceed their quotas.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that other options to ease the oil price
collapse will be discussed during the group's meeting in
next June.
</P>
<P>
Nasir ruled out the possibility of reversing OPEC's output
increase decision, saying "there was no going back" in this field.
</P>
<P>
World oil prices slumped from 1997's averaged 19.43
U.S. dollars a barrel to the current level of 14 to 15 dollars in
the past four months when fears grew that a flood of supply will
swamp the world oil market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
