<HEADLINE> Japan to Provide Emergency Aid to Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Japan will grant 300 billion yen
(about 2.4 billion U.S. dollars) in emergency loans to financially
strapped Indonesia, Kyodo news service reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The loans, to be provided by the Export-Import Bank of Japan,
will form the core of the package of measures that the Japanese
government and the ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) will put
together Friday.
</P>
<P>
The package is aimed at bringing Indonesian and other battered
Asian economies out of the currency and financial crisis, Kyodo
quoted government officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Finance Minister Hikaru Matsunaga will formally
announce the package when he attends a gathering of finance
ministers and central bankers for the Group of Seven (G-7) major
industrialized countries in London on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Another major step Japan will take is the expansion of the
government's credit line of trade insurance to Japanese exporters
doing business with Asian companies to 18 billion dollars, the
officials added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
