<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flaming Bulls Beats Rockets, Soaring Up To Top </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Shandong Flaming Bulls
overpowered league leaders August First Rockets 85-68 Wednesday in
the 20th round of the Hilton Chinese basketball first division
league.
</P>
<P>
The Flaming Bulls soared pass the defending Champion Rockets to
take over the top spot for the second time this season with 37
points from 17 wins in the 12-team tournament.
</P>
<P>
Storming back from 34-35 deficit at the break, the Flaming
Bulls made a series of dazzling baskets in the second half,
handling the Rockets their third lose this season with the biggest
margin in their franchise history.
</P>
<P>
Gong Xiaobin hit 33 points for the Flaming Bulls, who shot
34-47 from the fields, outplaying the three-time league champions,
who made merely 25 baskets from 58 attempts.
</P>
<P>
Liu Zhen sanked all his four three-pointers in the second half
for the Flaming Bulls who were 8-16 behind the arc.
</P>
<P>
Liu Yudong, the Rockets' aggressive power forward, made his
debut this season after having knee surgery last September but put
little pressure on either ends.
</P>
<P>
The Flaming Bulls dominated the boards with 31-17.
</P>
<P>
Uprising Shanghai Sharks stunned Liaoning Hunters 85-66 at
home, but made no change of their positions on the standings.
</P>
<P>
The Sharks, fourth with 32 points, outrebounded the Hunters
51-25. The 2.21-m center Yao Ming, a 17-year-old rookie, grabbed a
game high 17 rebounds for the Sharks.
</P>
<P>
But the Hunters, last year's runners-up, still maintained in
the third place with 35 points from a 15-5 records.
</P>
<P>
In the turnover-plagued match, the Sharks built a 17-point lead
in the first half at 39-22 and carried it to the final victory.
</P>
<P>
In Beijing, Lianhang Eagles and Zhejiang Squirrels, last two
teams in the 12-team league, fought for honor while the Eagles
edged their rivals 74-65.
</P>
<P>
In Wednesday's other matches, Guangdong Tigers defeated Jiangsu
Dragons 89-71, Jinan Pegasus ousted Shenyang Lions 77-60, and
Sichuan Pandas lost to the visiting Beijing Ducks 67-78. 
</P>
</TEXT>
