<HEADLINE> France Counts on U.N. Chief, Iraq to Reach Compromise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 18 (Xinhua) -- France said on Wednesday that it
is counting on United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan, who
will go to Baghdad on Friday, to reach a compromise with Iraq over
the method of inspecting eight presidential sites suspected of
hiding chemical and biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
"France is waiting for Iraq to show its will to find a
political and diplomatic way out of the crisis by making necessary
gestures,'' said French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Anne
Gazeau-Secret.
</P>
<P>
She said Annan has enough space to act in Baghdad by focusing
on obtaining an agreement with Iraq on the method of inspecting
the eight presidential sites.
</P>
<P>
France has suggested the United Nations send experts other
than those of the UNSCOM teams to join inspections of these sites.
</P>
<P>
Once he obtains an agreement with Iraq, Annan will present it
to the U.N. Security Council, said the French spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
She also said that France differs with Iraq over the method of
inspection, which was shown during the talks between President
Jacques Chirac and Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohamed Said al-Sahhaf
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Chirac warned Iraq that time for a diplomatic solution is
running out, although a diplomatic solution is still possible if
Iraq makes further concessions over weapons inspection.
</P>
<P>
In a television interview Wednesday, French Foreign Minister
Hubert Vedrine said it is likely that Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein will change his mind and make new concessions.
</P>
<P>
"It is not absurd to think that ... he can respond to what is
incessantly said, notably by France,'' said Vedrine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
