<HEADLINE> UK Defense Chief on Possible Military Strike on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 18 (Xinhua) -- British Defense Secretary
George Robertson said here Wednesday possible military strikes on
Iraq would inflict substantial damage on the country's military
capability.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a BBC radio interview, Robertson said that he was
confident that planned air strikes would deal a fatal blow to
Iraq's military ability.
</P>
<P>
"I rely on skilled and careful military advice, and all I can
say to you is that we are absolutely certain that the damage that
will be done to him (Saddam) and his military structure is going
to be very considerable indeed and that will substantially reduce
his capability of attacking his neighbors," Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
Robertson, whose country has sent one aircraft carrier and 18
war planes to the Gulf Region, stressed that force would be a last
resort to make Saddam comply with U.N. Security Council
resolutions that demand the destruction of Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
Britain, which strongly supports military action against Iraq,
has voiced a cautious welcome to the United Nations Secretary
General Kofi Annan's visit to Iraq later this week. 
</P>
