<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Sceptical About Signing of Investment Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 18 (Xinhua) -- France said Wednesday that it is
little likely the countries of the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development (OECD) can sign the Multilateral
Investment Accord by the end of April as is scheduled.
</P>
<P>
"France, as other participants in the negotiation, considers
that the respect of the technical deadline should not be imposed
at the expense of the quality and usefulness of the accord under
discussion," said French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Anne
Gazeau-Secret.
</P>
<P>
The Multilateral Investment Accord is aimed at liberalizing
investment criteria among the 29 member countries of the OECD with
the principle of non-discrimination between national and foreign
enterprises in investment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
The OECD members and the European Commission resumed the
two-year-old talks on the treaty on Monday in Paris amid protest
from French intellectuals who suspect that the United States is
trying to force its way into the European market through such an
accord.
</P>
<P>
France, Italy, Belgium and Canada have also set up a united
front to defend cultural exception of different nations, as was
guaranteed by the General Agreement on Tariff and Trade (GATT).
</P>
<P>
Ecologists and other non-government organizations of both
Europe and the United States have expressed fear about "social
dumping," as countries could lower environment protection
standards in order to draw investments.
</P>
<P>
Europe is also opposed to the U.S. extra-territorial laws such
as Helms-Burton Act and D'Amato-Kennedy Act, which ban foreign
companies from doing business with Cuba, Iran and Libya.
</P>
<P>
European Union countries are also reluctant to give up
"European preference" which allows European companies have
preferential treatment in making investment among European
partners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0028 </DOCNO>
