<HEADLINE> Cypriot President-Elect Invites All Parties to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, February 18 (Xinhua) -- President-elect Glafcos
Clerides of Cyprus has invited all political parties to join a new
government of national unity, a government spokesman said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"In view of his public position to form a government of
national unity, President Clerides considers it his duty to
address the parties in writing and invite them to participate,"
Manolis Christofides said at a daily press briefing.
</P>
<P>
Clerides was re-elected on Sunday for a second five-year
term. He has pledged to form a government of national unity and
has asked the parties to reply to his invitations this week,
according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
If there is no response from the parties, the president would
go ahead and form a cabinet which would be widely accepted,
Christofides added.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition left-wing Progress Party of the Working
People (AKEL), which supported Clerides' rival, former Foreign
Minister George Iacovou, in the presidential elections, has been
unwilling to participate in the new government.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot be part of such a government since there are
fundamental differences between us and the side Clerides
represents," AKEL's General Secretary Dimitris Christofias told a
press conference Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
But he said that AKEL would continue to work with the
government in the National Council to achieve maximum possible
unity as far as decisions on the peace process of Cyprus are
concerned.
</P>
<P>
The council is the top advisory body to Cypriot president for
the peace talks with the Turkish Cypriots controlling northern
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the Mediterranean
island after an abortive coup by the Greek Cypriots seeking union
with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The international community has been making efforts to help
reunify Cyprus in a bi-zonal and bi-communal formula. But no
tangible results have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
