<HEADLINE> Angolan Police Urged to Fight UNITA Militia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Andre Pitra Petroff, Angolan
Minister of the Interior, Wednesday called on police around the
country to take up action to fight militiamen of the former rebel
UNITA movement, the Angola News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Petroff made the call at the opening ceremony of the national
meeting of Angolan police.
</P>
<P>
According to him, militiamen of the National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) have been striking horror in
central Angola's Benguila province recently.
</P>
<P>
Over last weekend, the militiamen launched armed attack to
Capupa and Utalala town, killing five and wounding seven
seriously, said the report.
</P>
<P>
In the town of Lomaum, which was previously occupied by UNITA,
the report noted, armed militiamen killed a chief of a tribe for
the reason that he had been implementing policies of the ruling
People's Liberation Movement since local authority was
re-established in November 1997.
</P>
<P>
The fighters were engaged in a looting spree during their
evacuation. Although they were defeated by local police, they
had exerted negative influence to local people. 
</P>
