<HEADLINE> UK Pledges to Seek Full Iraqi Compliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 18 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair pledged here Wednesday his country would seek full Iraqi
compliance with U.N. Security Council resolutions on arms
inspection.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in British parliament Wednesday afternoon, Blair said
that he welcomed the planned visit to Iraq by U.N. Secretary
General Kofi Annan as a last-ditch effort to resolve the worsening
Gulf Crisis.
</P>
<P>
"We hope his mission will succeed. Whether or not it will
depend on Saddam Hussein," Blair said.
</P>
<P>
However, Blair, whose country maintains a tough position on the
U.N-Iraq standoff, made it clear that Annan's Baghdad mission is
within the following parameters:
</P>
<P>
"There must be full compliance with the U.N. Security Council
resolutions on weapons inspections; There must be no inhibition or
condition that prevents the inspectors gaining full access to the
sites that they need; there must be nothing that in any way
undermines the integrity of the weapons inspection process."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said in a
statement issued Wednesday afternoon that Annan's Baghdad visit
"represents the last chance to resolve this crisis by diplomatic
means."
</P>
<P>
"Our demand is straightforward: Iraq must comply with the
Resolutions of (U.N.) Security Council. Iraq must put in writing
any new agreement on access," Cook said in the statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
