<HEADLINE> ECOMOG May Stay in Sierra Leone for Six Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Chief of Defense
Staff Major-General Abdulsalam Abubakar has said that the west
African peace-keeping force ECOMOG may have to be in Sierra Leone
for the next six months to carry out the disarmament of
combatants.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar made the remarks at a meeting in New York with staff
of the Nigerian missions during his visit to the United Nations,
the News Agency of Nigeria reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The disarmament of all combatants, including soldiers of the
military junta led by Major Paul Johnny Koromah, is part of the
Conakry agreement, which provides that Koromah must return the
power to civilian President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah who was overthrown
by him in a coup last May.
</P>
<P>
Koromah, however, later insisted that his troops could not be
disarmed because they are the National Armed Forces of Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
After a week's fighting, the ECOMOG has captured Sierra
Leonean capital Freetown and is now in control of most part of
the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Abubakar said, "ECOMOG has broken the
backbone of the factions".
</P>
<P>
He defended ECOMOG's actions in Freetown by saying that the
sub-regional peace-keeping force was acting in defense of itself
against persistent attacks by Koromah's forces.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Liberia's protest over the arrest of fleeing
junta members by ECOMOG in Monrovia, Abubakar said the issue is
being addressed by the sub-regional body, the Economic Community
of West African States (ECOWAS).
</P>
<P>
Abubakar arrived in New York Sunday for a one-week visit to
the United Nations. He is expected to sign a memorandum of
understanding on Nigeria's contribution of troops to the U.S.
stand-by peace-keeping force.
</P>
<P>
The report said he has earlier met with U.S. officials on the
African crisis response initiatives suggested by Washington.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar also briefed the group of ECOWAS ambassadors to the
U.N. on developments in Sierra Leone and Liberia, as well as the
political situation in Nigeria, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
