<HEADLINE> Jordan Not to Open Airspace for Strike on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Jordan will not let other
countries to use its airspace to conduct air strikes against
Iraq, said a senior Jordanian official here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters after meeting with Israeli National
Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon, Jordanian Water and
Irrigation Minister Munther Haddadin said even if the U.S.-led
military attack on Iraq erupts, Jordan will not open its airspace
to any countries for military purposes.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian government knows how to protect its airspace and its
security, he said.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting earlier, the Jordanian minister conferred
with Sharon on joint water development projects in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian-Israeli relations had been damaged by the failed
assassination of a Hamas (Islamic Resistance Movement) leader,
Khaled Mashaal, in Amman last September by hit men of Israel's
intelligence agency Mossad. Haddadin was the first Jordanian
official to pay a short official visit to Israel since the
incident.
</P>
<P>
A committee appointed by Israeli government completed an
investigation of the bungled operation and submitted its report on
Tuesday. Israeli Foreign Ministry had sent a copy of the report to
the embassy in Amman the same day for immediate relay to the
royal palace.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu had conversation over
telephone with King Hussein Tuesday on the report and confirmed
with him the joint efforts to regain diplomatic momentum lost
because of the Mashaal incident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
