<HEADLINE> US Supports a Cyprus Settlement: Ambassador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The United States will take
advantage of the opportunities in 1998 to help reach a solution to
the protracted Cyprus problem, U.S. Ambassador to Cyprus Kenneth
Brill said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a meeting with Cypriot President-elect Glafcos
Clerides, Brill said that during the talks he conveyed President
Bill Clinton's warm congratulations to Clerides on his re-election.
</P>
<P>
Clerides was re-elected on Sunday for a second five-year term
in office in a narrow victory over his rival George Iacovou, a
former foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. is very serious about trying to take advantage of the
opportunities that 1998 provides" in efforts for a solution to the
Cyprus problem, Brill said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when
Turkey landed its troops and took over the northern third of the
island following a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the issue of Turkish Cypriot participation in
accession negotiations between Cyprus and the European Union
(EU), Brill stressed that "it is obviously better for that
accession process to start with a unified island rather than
otherwise."
</P>
<P>
The EU summit in Luxembourg last December reaffirmed its
decision to start membership talks with Cypriot government by the
end of next March, a stand angrily denounced by Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash has suspended bicommunal
activities and contacts since last December in retaliation for the
EU decision, and further threatened to seek union with Turkey if
the EU membership talks proceed as planned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
