<HEADLINE> Victim Friendly Courts Opened in Harare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Emmersom Mnangagwa, Zimbabwean
Minister of Justice, Legal and Parliamentary Affairs, Wednesday
officially opened the first victim friendly court in Harare.
</P>
<P>
"The establishment of the victim friendly court was a result
of the increase in the number of rape cases involving children,"
Mnangawa said.
</P>
<P>
"The children would often fail to speak in court or, when they
managed to speak, they broke down several times during the course
of the trial," he noted.
</P>
<P>
In the past some witnesses had failed to give evidence and
answer questions in conventional courts which resulted in the
discharge of the accused for lack of sufficient evidence.
</P>
<P>
The friendly courts were designed to protect rape victims from
being intimidated by their perpetrators when giving evidence.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the government would soon open
similar courts in all parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
The courts were established in 1997 under the Criminal
Procedure and Evidence Amendment Act.
</P>
<P>
Last year there were 2,567 rape cases reported in Zimbabwe,
with the capital Harare alone recording more than 140 involving
children.
</P>
<P>
The program was being boosted by a number of embassies and
non-governmental organisations which were providing special
machines and trained manpower. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
