<HEADLINE> UAE Approves 1998 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates
(UAE) has approved the federal budget for 1998, putting this
year's deficit at some 480 million U.S. dollars, the official Wam
news agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This figure was about 70 percent more than the deficit of 280
million dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Wam quoted Mohammed Khalfan bin Kharbash, minister of state for
financial and industrial affairs, as saying this was due to an
increase in expenditure estimated at 5.84 billion dollars,
compared with 5.43 billion dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The revenues in 1998 were put at the level of 5.36 billion
dollars, up from 5.15 billion dollars last year, the minister
said.
</P>
<P>
Kharbash gave no detailed figures of the projected oil income,
which accounted for nearly two thirds of the tiny Gulf country's
total revenues in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
But informed sources from the ministry said the UAE expected
little change in this field. Oil exports earned the UAE 3.5
billion dollars last year when oil prices averaged 19.43 dollars a
barrel.
</P>
<P>
World oil prices slumped to the current level of 14 to 15
dollars a barrel after the Organization of the Petroleum Exporting
Countries decided to increase its output ceiling by 10 percent to
27.5 million barrel per day starting January this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
