<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Economy Increases 3.78 Percent in 1997: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian economy
increased by 3.78 percent in 1997, the country's Federal Office
of Statistics (FOS) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The growth, measured at the 1984 constant price, was
attributed to that in the primary sector comprising agricultural
crops, livestock, forestry and fishing, the News Agency of
Nigeria reported.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, the primary sector grew by 4.22
percent, mining and quarrying sector by 8.23 percent,
manufacturing by 0.8 percent, distributive trade by 0.5 percent
and other sectors by 3.13 percent.
</P>
<P>
In terms of contribution by the five sectors to last year's
Gross Domestic Product (GDP), FOS said, the primary sector took a
share of 32.72 percent, but the largest contributor was the crude
oil and gas sector which accounted for 41.36 percent.
</P>
<P>
Wholesale and retail trade contributed 13.27 percent,
manufacturing 4.77 percent and other sectors 7.88 percent.
</P>
<P>
While export rose from 25.49 percent in 1996 to 26.71 percent
in 1997, import also increased from 20.54 percent to 20.69
percent, FOS said.
</P>
<P>
It further disclosed that household consumption had an 82.58
percent share in the 1997 GDP, compared with 84.07 percent in the
previous year. 
