<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait expressed its best
wish Wednesday that the United Nations Secretary General Kofi
Annan would succeed in his efforts to end the current Iraq crisis
peacefully during an upcoming visit to Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Sheikh Sabah
Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah was quoted by Kuwait News Agency as saying that
"the visit which is comprehensively supported by the Security
Council members gives hope that Iraq listens to the voice of
reason and peace."
</P>
<P>
It gives hope that Iraq "complies with the international will
in honoring and fully implementing Security Council resolutions in
order to spare its country and people all of these repercussions,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that "the success of the U.N. Secretary General's
endeavor would contribute to opening a broader path for peace,
security and stability in the region."
</P>
<P>
Annan said Wednesday in New York that he is leaving for Baghdad
Thursday to begin two days of talks aimed at resolving the crisis
that has developed over Iraq's refusal to allow an unconditional
and unfettered U.N. arms inspections of mass destruction weapons
in that country.
</P>
<P>
He said he has the full support of all the Security Council
members to seek a diplomatic solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait, which was occupied in 1990-91 by Iraq for seven
months, had repeatedly voiced support to a diplomatic solution to
the U.N.-Iraq stand-off over the arms inspection operations while
provides bases for thousands of American troops and a dozen of
F-117A stealth fighter bombers in preparation of a possible
U.S. military strike against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait pins high hopes on a success of Annan's Baghdad trip
which would avert a military action that might cause retaliatory
Iraqi attacks against it. 
</P>
