<HEADLINE> Iran, Iraq, France Discuss Iraq Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi discussed the latest developments of the crisis over
United Nations arms inspections in Iraq respectively with his
Iraqi and French counterparts on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with visiting Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammad
Saeed al-Sahhaf, Kharrazi called for coordinated diplomatic
efforts to implement the U.N. Security Council resolutions in a
way that "dignity and prestige of the Iraqi people will be
preserved."
</P>
<P>
He stressed Iran's belief that the implementation of the U.N.
resolutions needs no force, rather it will be possible through
Iraq's cooperation with the U.N. arms inspectors overseeing the
elimination of Iraq's weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The United States has threatened to take military actions to
force Iraq to grant full and unfettered access to all sites
suspected of hiding nuclear, chemical and biological weapons and
long-range missiles to launch them.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahhaf, who arrived in Tehran Wednesday morning, called on
Iran, chairman of the Organization of the Islamic Conference, to
continue support for a diplomatic solution to the Iraq crisis and
head off a possible U.S. attack on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
During a telephone consultation about the issue, Kharrazi and
French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine expressed hope that U.N.
chief Kofi Annan would succeed in mediating a political settlement
for the Iraq crisis during his trip to Baghdad on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Annan has reportedly won the consent of the five permanent
members of the U.N. Security Council - China, France, Russia, the
United States and Britain - to pay a visit to Iraq, which is
believed to be the last-ditch effort to defuse the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers urged Iraq to comply with the U.N. Security
Council resolutions to avert possible air strike by the United
States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
