<HEADLINE> Tanzania Accuses Foreign Embassies of Backing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 18 (Xinhua) - Tanzania Wednesday
accuses some foreign embassies of backing youths who joined other
Moslems in last week's bloody riots near a mosque in Dar es
Salaam which left two killed by the armed policemen.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Minister of Home Affairs Ali Ameir Mohamed told a
press conference that Tanzania was aware that some youths were
being used by some foreign embassies here to further the
Fundamental course, but he declined to identify them.
</P>
<P>
"We are aware that some youths are being used by some
embassies to create chaos and disharmony in the country," he
said, adding that "I can assure you that we are seriously
monitoring this."
</P>
<P>
The minister also attributed the riots to some opposition
political parties in Zanzibar and the mainland with a view to
promote their own interests.
</P>
<P>
He warned that Tanzania is warily thinking of striking off
some religious organizations which are busy sowing seeds of
animosity and chaos to threaten the country's peace, stability
and unity.
</P>
<P>
Ameir Mohamed stressed that the government was not against
Moslems but some sects which use the religion to enhance their
ulterior motives.
</P>
<P>
"The government respects the freedom of worship and doesn't
discriminate upon any denomination so long as that denomination
doesn't ridicule another religious sect."
</P>
<P>
The Dar es Salaam Regional Police Commander Alfred Gewe said
Tuesday that the area near the down town Mwembe Chai Mosque,
where two people were killed last Friday when the armed police
quenched a Moslem-led riot, has become peaceful.
</P>
<P>
"There are no reported incidents of unrest throughout the
city," Gewe said.
</P>
<P>
Witness said that uniformed police officers, armed with
sub-machines guns, kept a distance from the mourners in an
apparent way to avoid provoking them into a riot.
</P>
<P>
"If they had rioted and destroyed vehicles or looted like they
had done before, we would have hit hard," one police official was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The police killed two people in the first bloody riot since
Tanzania's independence in 1961 from the British colonial rule
last Friday when they tried to disperse a mob of some 2,000 near
the Mwembe Chai Mosque.
</P>
<P>
The violence erupted last Thursday when the Moslems protested
the detention of their leader by destroying dozens of vehicles
and stoned the approaching police.
</P>
<P>
Police forced their way into the mosque and arrested some 130
of the rioters including women and children who fled there for
protection.
</P>
<P>
The rioters detained have appeared in two groups in the Kisutu
Resident Magistrate's court, facing charges of destroying
properties and physically harming people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
