<HEADLINE> Deutsche Bank Profits Down in 1997 due to Asian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Germany's largest bank, Deutsche
Bank, Wednesday said in Frankfurt its profits in 1997 dropped by
one-third to 4.0 billion marks (2.19 billion U.S. dollars) due to
the financial crisis in Asia.
</P>
<P>
According to the bank's spokesman Walter Schumacher, the effect
of the Asian crisis became apparent in the final quarter of last
year.
</P>
<P>
Three weeks ago, the bank announced that it had provided an
additional 1.4 billion marks to its risk provisions for the
business in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Being affected by the Asian crisis, the bank for the first time
had been prevented from setting aside reserves last year. It added
1.2 billion marks to its reserves in 1995, and 1.4 billion marks
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Deutsche Bank's balance sheet total for the first
time exceeded the trillion mark level, reaching 1.1 trillion
marks, an increase of 18 percent over 1996.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on a press report that Deutsche Bank was
interested in acquiring Belgium's largest institute, General Bank
NV, Schumacher quoted management board chairman Rolf Breuer as
saying recently that such merger was "no topic" for the bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
