<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Asked to Launch Travelers Check Sooner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) has been called for the launching of the
much-awaited ECOWAS traveler cheque "without further delay".
</P>
<P>
The regional financial instrument was at first scheduled for
launching last December, but ECOWAS has to keep from issuance due
to reservations of the Francophone member states over the debt
owed by two members.
</P>
<P>
A planned ceremony to ECOWAS Chairman General Sani Abacha, who
is also Nigeria's head of state, to launch the scheme was also
stalled at a mini-summit on the creation of the ECOWAS single
monetary zone, which was held in past two days.
</P>
<P>
The reason of the failure this time, according to Nigerian
Finance Minister Anthony Ani, is "the inability of some heads of
state to arrive for the launching" in Abuja, capital of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Now that the travelers cheque is designed as the first step
toward a single monetary zone in west Africa by the year 2000,
finance ministers and central bank governors at the meeting seem
impatient with the development.
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued by the ECOWAS executive secretariat
today, they recommended to the ECOWAS authority "the ECOWAS
travelers cheque should be launched without further delay".
</P>
<P>
According to Ani, the two member countries, Liberia and Guinea
Bissau, owe the ECOWAS clearing system a total of some 20 million
U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The press release did not say when authorities concerned would
discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS travelers cheque is a new payment instrument to be
issued by member central banks to help facilitate the settlement
of both financial and commercial transactions within the
sub-region.
</P>
<P>
Some five million travelers checks have been printed for the
take-off of the scheme.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
