<HEADLINE> A Sydney Flu Hits Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 18 (Xinhua) -- A nasty new flu bug, first
identified in Sydney, Australia, last year, is racing across
Canada, a report said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The virulent flu strain, dubbed A Sydney, is being blamed for
dozens of nursing home deaths, clogged emergency rooms and
sparcely attended classrooms and offices across the country.
</P>
<P>
The strain will eventually affect 25 percent of the population,
according to regional health officials in the Ottawa area, which
is suffering a significant outbreak.
</P>
<P>
Some 175 children turned up in the emergency ward in one
children's hospital here one night last week.
</P>
<P>
The flu has also played a role in eight deaths at local nursing
homes, the Globe and Mail newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
In the city of Winnipeg, it's believed that the strain is
responsible for five deaths at one nursing home.
</P>
<P>
The Toronto Health Department also reports "widespread
outbreaks" in the Toronto area, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Like any flu bug, A Sydney's symptoms include aches, pains,
coughs and fevers. It usually causes fevers lasting three to four
days and fatigue that hangs up to a month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
