<HEADLINE> Insurance Fees on Ships Passing Gulf Not Raised </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, February 18 (Xinhua) -- International insurance
companies will not increase the charges of marine insurance fees
on ships and tankers passing through the Gulf region as a result
of the current tension flared up by the Iraq-U.N. stand-off over
arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
This was announced Wednesday by Hjaj Bou Khdour, deputy
chairman of Contracts and Purchases in the Kuwait-based United
Arab Marine Shipping Company.
</P>
<P>
The sea route of ships sailing to and from Kuwait "will be safe
as it would be far from the theater of operations in case Iraq was
targeted with a military strike," Bou Khdour was quoted by Kuwait
News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
"There are no fears on safety of ships and tankers entering
the Kuwaiti territorial waters because these waters will remain
absolutely safe," he said.
</P>
<P>
Since 1991, no additional insurance premiums have been imposed
on the ships' hull and the cargoes against war risks in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Although three weeks have passed since the Iraq-U.N. crisis
flared up, the international insurance companies have not raised
the insurance fees on ships and tankers heading to and from the
Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
Bou Khdour affirmed that the movement of ships to and
from the Kuwaiti ports has been normal.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait is expected to receive 10,000 container vessels and
125 ships this month compared with the same number of
containers and ships received in January, Bou Khdour said.
</P>
<P>
He anticipated that even if a U.S. military strike against
Iraq comes true, the insurance fees for ships passing the
Gulf would not be raised. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
