UNITED NATIONS, February 18 (Xinhua) -- the U.N. Security
Council on Wednesday gave its full support to U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan for his trip to Baghdad to solve the
current crisis relating to arms inspections in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
This was expressed in a statement read by council President
Gabon's Denis Dangue Rewake after the council heard Annan's
briefing on his consultations with the council's five permanent
members since last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The "Permanent Five" achieved unanimity to endorse Annan's
visit on Tuesday and he is expected to be in Baghdad on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Rewaka said the 15 member council expressed its complete
confidence in Annan's ability to find ways and means of resolving
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Appearing together before the press, Annan said he is happy on
the council's unanimity.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that he was prepared for the task which he termed
as "difficult".
</P>
<P>
"I have made it clear that a trip has to be prepared very
carefully, both here and in Baghdad," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also said he has talked with U.S. President Bill Clinton and
has had contacts with Iraqi officials.
</P>
<P>
His discussion with Clinton was "very long", "very
constructive" and "useful", covering "all the aspects of the Iraqi
crisis", Annan said, adding that Clinton "is repeating, as others
have done, that they (the United States) would prefer a diplomatic
solution".
</P>
<P>
"I am also encouraged by the message coming from Baghdad that
they are prepared to engage me constructively to find a solution,"
the Secretary-General said, looking confident.
</P>
<P>
"I think they (Iraq) have indicated they are serious and they
are looking forward to these discussions with me, and that they
will do whatever they can to make this (trip) successful", he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
