<HEADLINE> Greece: Annan's Visit to Baghdad,  Positive Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Greece described Wednesday the
forthcoming visit to Iraq by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan as
"a positive development," saying that it wished the U.N. chief's
mission a success.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas said Annan's visit to Iraq aimed at persuading
Baghdad to allow U.N. weapons inspections was a positive
development.
</P>
<P>
Athens hoped for a successful outcome of Annan's mission, which
already won full Security Council support, he added.
</P>
<P>
As for the current Iraqi crisis caused by Baghdad's blocking of
U.N. arms inspections, Reppas said that Greece was opposed to any
country producing, possessing or using chemical or nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos and
visiting Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov contacted with
their counterparts of France, Germany and Belgium to promote
Annan's visit to Baghdad which is expected to take place Friday.
</P>
<P>
After their talks in Athens Monday, Pangalos and Primakov
expressed their opposition to the use of force against Iraq,
saying that the possibilities of a political solution to the Iraqi
crisis were not exhausted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
