<HEADLINE> Kabbah Meets Cabinet, Parliament Members for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leonean President Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah Wednesday held a meeting with members of his cabinet and the
parliament in Guinea, where he has lived in exile since his ousting in
a coup last May, to discuss his return.
</P>
<P>
The president briefed the audience on his consideration of
government policies for building a new Sierra Leone after the return,
the British Broadcasting Corporation reported Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
Among other things, the president said, the only way out for Sierra
Leone is by avoiding the politics of confrontation, destruction,
suspicion and notorious pulling-down syndrome.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to the opposition of "such a large bureaucracy" in the
Sierra Leonean government, Kabbah announced he would be restructuring
his cabinet, ostentatiously downsizing it and streamlining the
government bureaucracy, the report said.
</P>
<P>
On his return, the president said, he will set up a policy advisory
council that will review cabinet documents and evaluate the
performance of government ministries.
</P>
<P>
However, some leaders of the parliament told him they have no such
intention at present, which seems to put the comeback plan into
chopping waters.
</P>
<P>
The Committee of Five on Sierra Leone, a special body under the
Economic Community of West African States, is now in Freetown to
assess the situation in the country so as to fix a date for Kabbah to
return.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations special envoy to Sierra Leone, Francis Okello,
is also there for relevant matters.
</P>
<P>
Kabbah himself has already set up a task force after the fall of
the junta in Freetown to make preparations for his return, which,
reports said, might take place in the next one or two weeks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
