<HEADLINE> Malaria Becomes No. 1 Killer in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan health authorities
announced Wednesday that malaria, which killed 3,590 last year,
has become number one killer in the country.
</P>
<P>
Dysentery is the second killer which claimed more than 2,000
lives, with most of those died were under the age five.
</P>
<P>
Statistics issued by the authorities show that 506,840 people
were caught by malaria#,125,800 of them serious in 1997.
</P>
<P>
While the civil war, which ruined most of the health
institutions in the country, is labeled as the root of the
diseases, the heavy rains and poor sanitation conditions are said
to be the main reason for the spread of the disease.
</P>
<P>
The statistics said the civil war has destroyed about 60
percent of the health institutions in the country, and four
million of the 11 million population in the country are suffering
from parasitic diseases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
