<HEADLINE> Iran Calls on Iraq to Implement UN Resolutions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami Wednesday called on Iraq to implement the United Nations
Security Council resolutions to "neutralize any ulterior motives"
of the United States.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammad Saeed
al-Sahhaf, Khatami said the U.S. has a history of interference in
the affairs of the Gulf region, and any possible military attack
on Iraq would be against the regional interest.
</P>
<P>
He was referring the U.S. threat to take military actions to
force Iraqi compliance with the U.N. arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
According to the Islamic Republic News Agency, Khatami voiced
hope during the meeting that the visit of U.N. Secretary General
Kofi Annan to Baghdad Friday would help find a peaceful solution
to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
He expressed sympathy for the sufferings of Iraqi people, who
have been under the crippling economic sanctions imposed by the
U.N. in 1990 after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Iran, as chairman of the Organization of the Islamic
Conference, would continue its efforts to find a diplomatic
solution to the crisis, Khatami said.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahhaf briefed Khatami on the standoff between Iraq and the
U.N. Special Commission in charge of eliminating Iraq's weapons of
mass destruction, U.S. threat to attack Iraq and Baghdad's efforts
to head off the possible attack.
</P>
<P>
He appreciated Iran's efforts to help defuse the crisis, and
called for a continuation of the efforts.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi foreign minister arrived here Wednesday morning and
has held talks with his Iranian counterpart Kamal Kharrazi on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi rejected the use of force under the pretext of
implementing the U.N. Security Council resolutions and called for
coordinated diplomatic efforts to preserve "dignity and prestige
of the Iraqi people." 
</P>
</TEXT>
