<HEADLINE> More Foreign Direct Investment Pumps into S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The amount of foreign direct
investment (FDI) pumping into South Africa was on the increase, Trade
and Industry Minister Alec Erwin told parliament Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
FDI increased to 13.6 billion Rand (2.7 billion U.S. Dollars) last
year from 4.9 billion (about one billion dollars) in 1994, the SABC
television quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
Over the four-year period, the United States was the biggest
investor, followed by Britain, Malaysia, Japan and Germany.
</P>
<P>
Owing to a low savings rate in the country, South Africa relies
heavily on foreign capital. Experts say it needs 4.6 to six billion
dollars every year to spur its economy.
</P>
<P>
Erwin said foreign investment was welcome but the government had to
keep its eyes open on foreign speculative investment in order to avoid
financial upheavals as in Southeast Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
