<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Not Optimistic on Annan's Iraq Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The United States Wednesday
showed little optimism about a breakthrough to be achieved by U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan during his talks with Iraqi officials
in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry flatly answered with "No" a
reporter who asked if the White House was optimistic about any
possible breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
But McCurry said Annan's mission to find a diplomatic way to
solve the current crisis is still "important."
</P>
<P>
"There's been no indication from the government of Iraq that
would lend anyone to be optimistic," McCurry said. "There has been
only obstinacy, concealment and deliberate lies about past
practices."
</P>
<P>
Annan won approval from the five permanent members of the U.N.
Security Council Tuesday to go to Baghdad in an effort to avert a
U.S. military action against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether there were U.S. objections to a possible
compromise in which diplomats from council members would accompany
the U.N. inspection team, McCurry said, "There's only our firm
view and now the view of the Security Council that relevant
Security Council resolutions must be adhered to, that there must
be a process by which UNSCOM (U.N. Special Commission) can do its
work in Iraq, and that the integrity of that process which has
worked so well over the last seven years must be maintained."
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday morning, U.S. envoy to the United Nations
Bill Richardson told NBC in an interview that the United States
could accept the proposal but on the condition that "the Iraqis
accept clear access to all sites unconditionally."
</P>
<P>
"In terms of diplomats, observers, that would observe the U.N.
inspection team itself, I think that is something we can deal
with," Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
"If the Iraqis accept clear access to all sites
unconditionally, which they have not done, if they stop
politicizing the U.N. inspection team and give them the
professionalism and integrity and the ability to go anywhere they
wanted at any time, they may get themselves out of this box," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Richardson said that did not mean the United States was backing
down from its previous calls for clear, unfettered access for the
inspectors in searching sites that the Iraqi government deemed
sensitive and thus off-limits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
