<HEADLINE> Annan: He Will Stay in Baghdad as Long as Mission Takes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 18 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said Wednesday that he will stay in Baghdad as long as
his peace mission takes.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that I would not have to stay very long, but I will
stay as long as it takes," he said.
</P>
<P>
Annan made the remarks after he briefed the full Security
Council on his recent consultations with the council's five
permanent members, which produced an endorsement for his trip to
find ways of resolving the crisis relating to arms inspections in
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Annan said he was prepared for the "difficult" task and he
thought that the Iraqi officials "have indicated they are serious"
about Annan's mediation efforts.
</P>
<P>
"I am also encouraged by the message coming from Baghdad that
they are prepared to engage me constructively to find a solution,"
he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
According to his spokesman, Annan is leaving Thursday and is
expected to be in the Iraqi capital Friday.
</P>
<P>
On his way to Baghdad, he is going to make a stopover in Paris
to meet with French President Jacques Chirac Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Annan's itinerary schedule prepared by his office shows that he
is expected to end his trip on February 23.
</P>
<P>
His seven aides on the trip include his special envoy to
Afghanistan Lakhdar Brahimi, Johan Molander from Sweden's Foreign
Ministry, and U.N. Under-Secretary-General for the Office of Legal
Affairs Hans Corell. 
</P>
</TEXT>
