<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Richardson on U.S. Goals of UN Chief's Mission to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 18 (Xinhua) -- There should be no
deals, no compromises in UN Secretary-General's forthcoming visit
to Baghdad, Bill Richardson, the Ambassador of the United States
to the United Nations said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Richardson made the remarks after UN chief Kofi Annan briefed
the Security Council members of the United Nations this morning on
his four rounds of consultations on the current Iraqi crisis with
the permanent five.
</P>
<P>
The Ambassador said the United States feels very strongly the
goals of the mission should be very clear, and the goals are: to
enforce the resolutions of the UN Security Council and get Iraq
into full compliance; free, unconditional and unfetered access to
all sites by UN weapons inspectors and the complete integrity and
inviolability of the United Nations Special Commission.
</P>
<P>
Richardson said the United States reserve the right to oppose
any arrangement that does not protect the Security Council
resolutions and what is perceived as the national interests of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Saying he fully supported the UN Secretary-General and and a
diplomatic solution, Richardson said the problem is in Iraq, which
violates the will of the international community.
</P>
<P>
The Unites States has completed an extensive naval, air and
troop buildup in the Gulf, ready to strike if Iraq continues to
bar presidential sites to inspectors of the United Nations Special
commission in charge of dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief has been under pressure to make a mediation trip
to Iraq in order to solve the crisis peacefully. He announced to
go to Baghdad Tuesday after he got full support from the five
permanent members of UN Security Council, namely China, Russia,
France, Britain and the United states.  
</P>
</TEXT>
