<HEADLINE> 20 Countries to Take Part in S.Africa's Air Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 18 (Xinhua) -- At least 150 international
exhibitors from 20 countries would take part in an international air
show in Pretoria in April, organizers said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Dubbed Aerospace Africa '98, the show would feature air displays by
several exotic military and civil aircraft, show chairman Peter Piggott
told reporters in Pretoria, executive capital of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Countries taking part in include the United States, Britain, France,
Italy, Germany, Russia, Japan and Poland.
</P>
<P>
He said the show would also exhibit defense equipment short-listed
by South Africa for its two billion dollar defense renewal
program, which includes the purchase of light fighter aircraft and
helicopters.
</P>
<P>
The organizer said the show was about all aspects of the aviation
and aerospace industry. It was the first to be organized jointly by the
commercial aviation associations of Southern Africa and South Africa's
aerospace, maritime and defense-related industries.
</P>
<P>
Of special interest to Africa, Piggott said, would be the exhibition
of products needed to upgrade aviation systems on the continent. A
number of African delegations were also expected to visit the show.
</P>
<P>
African countries are under pressure to upgrade their air traffic
control systems in view of an international outcry on the dangers of
flying over the continent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
