<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Promises Loans to Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Managing Director of
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) Michel Camdessus has
announced that the IMF will offer loans to Russia in keeping with
an earlier schedule.
</P>
<P>
The Russian presidential press service said that during the
meeting with Russian president Boris Yeltsin Thursday Camdessus
proposed that Russia consider extending the current lending
agreement until the end of 1999 as part of an additional credit
line. The proposal met with a positive reply from the president.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin at the meeting expressed the determination of the
Russian authorities to follow the policy of reforms proceeding
from national interests.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Asian financial crisis, Yeltsin said Russia
would be able to protect its financial markets best by advancing
reforms and making tough financial decisions.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus said that the major cause of the Asian crisis was the
merger of big business and government institutions, special
privileges given by government to big business and the absence of
transparency.
</P>
<P>
Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin on Wednesday had
talks with Camdessus on questions relating to the program of
cooperation between Russia and the International Monetary Fund in
1998.
</P>
<P>
The IMF Managing Director noted that in the process of its
integration in the world economy Russia must protect itself from
the turmoils which arise on the world markets from time to time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
