<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Show on Chinese Culture in Eyes of American Artists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 19 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Ambassador to China
Jim Sasser held an exhibition in the ambassador's residence this
evening of paintings, prints, and sculpture meant to chronicle the
changes in American views of China over the past one hundred and
fifty years.
</P>
<P>
On display were 15 lithographs of "Chinese Ceramics from the
Collection of W.T.Walters"; "7 Characters: Light, Change, Trunk,
Individual, Howl, Truth, and Red Heart", collages of custom-made
paper, silk, embossed calligraphy, and advertisements; "Cow and
Trees", with a lyricism, calmness, and rich but subdued colors
that reveal affinities with Chinese painting; and "Yi" (one), a
horizontal stroke made by a bar of lead imbedded in beeswax.
</P>
<P>
These reflections on style were meant as a testimony to the
extraordinary impact of Chinese art on American creativity,
according to the ambassador and his wife.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xuehai, a Chinese oil painter who was among the dozens of
people to visit the show this evening, said that, if one oil
painting "Statuette and Vase" (1925) reflects China as mere symbol
in Chinese figurines and ceramics, a 1982 work, "7 Characters",
can suggest that the painter has a fairly good understanding of
Chinese art and philosophy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
