<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S'pore Says to Help Indonesia According to Ability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Singapore will continue to
help Indonesia to tide over the current economic turmoil but will
only do so within the limits of its own ability, Deputy Prime
Minister Lee Hsien Loong said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Lee Hsien Loong, who is also chairman of the Monetary Authority
of Singapore (MAS), Singapore's de facto central bank, said
Singapore is also helping to work on a Trade Guarantee Scheme for
Indonesia imports.
</P>
<P>
The scheme was put forward because major banks no longer
provide trade financing for Indonesian firms, making it almost
impossible for them to import goods and raw materials.
</P>
<P>
The proposed guarantee scheme is to give confidence to foreign
banks to accept letters of credit issued by Indonesian banks.
</P>
<P>
Under the scheme, the central banks of several countries will
jointly counter-guarantee the one made by Bank Indonesia, but this
will only cover sovereign risks, Lee told parliament.
</P>
<P>
He said the scheme will assure the other central banks that
Bank Indonesia will honor its own guarantee and the scheme will
operate for a maximum of two years.
</P>
<P>
Lee said the two billion U.S. dollars that the MAS will pledge
towards the scheme will be from the five billion U.S. dollars
Singapore promised earlier.
</P>
<P>
He assured the parliament that though the loan still stands, it
is structured like a back-up credit to supplement the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) program.
</P>
<P>
However, he added that Singapore is still in discussion with
other countries about the scheme, which will proceed only when six
to 12 countries agree to participate. The IMF and the World Bank
will have to support the scheme.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
