<HEADLINE> Russian Communists Demand Urgent Roundtable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Russian Communist Party leaders
Thursday demanded a roundtable be held urgently to discuss the
current situation in the country, according to the Interfax news
agency.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with Russian Premier Viktor Chernomyrdin, Leaders
of the Communist Party of Russia Gennady Zyuganov, Valentin
Kuptsov and Sergei Reshulsky complained that roundtable meetings
were not regular and that the issue of private savings devalued at
the start of economic reform had not been solved.
</P>
<P>
According to Zyuganov, the issues of energy and railroad
tariffs have not been discussed, supervisory boards at the ORT and
RTR television channels have not begun working, and the situation
with science and education has not improved.
</P>
<P>
Zyuganov said he had demanded that a government commission be
created to investigate "massive gross violations of legislation"
and his colleagues had urged the prime minister to increase
efforts for a peaceful settlement of the Iraq crisis.
</P>
<P>
The communist party leader said, "We welcome U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan's coming trip to Iraq, but we believe
that Russia should hold more intensive consultations with China,
Germany, France and Arab countries, which might play a positive
role for a peaceful settlement of the situation with Iraq."
</P>
