<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Sets Up Panel on Retrenched Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, February 19 (Xinhua) -- In anticipation of more
workers being laid off in the on-going economic turmoil in the
region, the Singapore government will set up a tripartite panel on
retrenched workers within the Ministry of Labor, the ministry said
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Labor said the establishment of the panel came
in the light of several major retrenchments by electronics
companies in recent months and in anticipation that more workers
would be laid off as a result of uncertain economic conditions.
</P>
<P>
The panel will advise the ministry on developing a network to
obtain timely information on impending retrenchment and to source
for job vacancies to facilitate the re-employment of those
retrenched.
</P>
<P>
The panel will also encourage employers contemplating
retrenchment to explore alternatives like redevelopment, shorter
work-week and adjustment of wage costs under the flexible wage
systems.
</P>
<P>
It will also help employers take advantage of training
incentives to upgrade workers' skills during the lull period.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the panel will enable the Employment Service
Department and the Labor Relations Department of the ministry to
better assist the retrenched workers.
</P>
<P>
The 10-member panel comprises representatives from the Ministry
of Labor, the National Trade Union Congress, the Singapore
National Employers Federation, the Economic Development Board, and
the Singapore Productivity and Standards Board. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
