<HEADLINE> Returned Tibetans Celebrate Tibetan New Year In Lhasa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, February 19 (Xinhua) -- More than 80 returned Tibetans
and relatives of overseas Tibetan today attended a reception to
celebrate the Tibetan New Year, which falls on February 27.
</P>
<P>
They said they appreciate the great changes taking place in
Tibet and the ethnic minority and religious policies of the
Communist Party at a reception that was held by the United Front
Department of the CPC Tibetan Autonomous Region Committee.
</P>
<P>
"I have witnessed the great changes in my hometown under the
correct leadership of the CPC since I returned more than a decade
ago," said Yexe Doje, a member of the Lhasa Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference, and concluded,
"If it were not for the CPC, there would not be a prosperous new
Tibet."
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Tibet had a GDP of 7.35 billion yuan, up by ten
percent from the previous year, the executive vice chairman of the
autonomous region said, and went on to say that the reunification
of the motherland is the aspiration of the Chinese, and the Dalai
Lama is still trying to get independence while pretending to favor
negotiations, and attempting to internationalize the Tibet issue.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that returned Tibetans and relatives of
overseas Tibetans will better understand Chinese history and
socialism, and contribute to Tibet's stability, development and
social progress.  
</P>
</TEXT>
