<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Religious Leaders Visit Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai's Mayor Xu Kuangdi,
in a meeting today with a delegation of US religious leaders led
by Rabbi Arthur Schneier of the Appeal of Conscience Foundation,
said he hopes their visit will help increase exchanges and
contacts between the clergy of China and the US.
</P>
<P>
The mayor briefed the visitors on the city's economic growth,
religious freedom, and protection of religious structures over the
past few years.
</P>
<P>
Rabbi Schneier said that Shanghai has done a lot to protect
religious sites in the course of construction and development.
</P>
<P>
The delegation arrived here yesterday evening from Nanjing, and
visited the East China Protestant Theological Seminary this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has 700,000 Buddhists, Taoists, Moslems, Catholics,
and Christians, and more than 250 religious sites.
</P>
<P>
It has also set up religious services in English in order
to provide convenience to foreigners in the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
