<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Starting Global Mapping Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 19 (Xinhua) -- China will start some projects
this year as part of the International Steering Committee for
Global Mapping's world map plan, the State Bureau of Surveying and
Mapping said today.
</P>
<P>
It includes data on China's administrative divisions,
topography, vegetation, and updating information about cities and
their surrounding areas with satellite imaging, said Yang Kai, the
Bureau's deputy-director.
</P>
<P>
He said the plan to develop a global map started with a world
environment and development conference in 1995. It will provide
geographic data for studying global environmental problems,
reducing the damages of natural disasters, and maintaining
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The plan will have two moves, the first, various countries
using data to develop a preliminary global map by the year 2000,
and second, international organizations updating the map with
satellite imaging and data on land and vegetation, Yang
explained. Then it will be updated every five years.
</P>
<P>
The International Steering Committee for Global Mapping was
established in 1996 to get various countries to develop a global
map. According to its general plan, China, Japan, the Republic of
Korea, Malaysia, and some European countries will be responsible
for mapping Asia and Europe.
</P>
<P>
China's participation means expanding international exchanges
and contributing to the sustainable development of the global
economy, Yang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
