<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Wins Women's 500m Short Track Speed Skating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Annie Perreault of Canada,
with the help of her teammate world record holder Isabelle Charest,
outskated her Chinese rivals to win the women's 500m short track speed
skating race here Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian was clocked 46.556 seconds for the crown. Yang Yang
(s) of China was second at 46.627. Chun Lee-kyung of South Korea,
competing in final B, was third at 46.335.
</P>
<P>
In the race of final A, Chinese skater Wang Chunlu led from the
starting point till the final curve.
</P>
<P>
After three legs skating, Charest, an experienced skater, sped up
from behind and tried to overskate Wang at the bending from the inner
side of the rink.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian displayed an outstanding technique in the race.  At
the moment to overskate Wang, Isabelle slipped down and tripped the
Chinese skater, who was just at the edge of the gold.
</P>
<P>
Perreault, who was then at the third place, took the opportunity
the cross the finishing line for the crown.
</P>
<P>
"I feel like a dream. I can't believe it," said Perreault. "It's
incredible."
</P>
<P>
Wang Chunlu, who was obviously angered by the case, did not finish
the race. Isabelle was disqualified for impedding.
</P>
<P>
Chun Lee-kyung, who was first in final B, was upgraded to take the
bronze medal.
</P>
<P>
For Yang Yang (s), who was making her second Olympic appearance,
was happy with the silver. "I am happy with the result, but I am
sorry for my teammate, who had a chance to win the gold," she said.
</P>
<P>
China has took part in six Winter Olympics since 1980 and is yet to
win a gold. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0108 </DOCNO>
