<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E. Africa to Adopt New Strategy for Better Human </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda,
the three members of the East Africa Cooperation (EAC), will
adopt a joint strategy aimed at improving human settlement
conditions in the region.
</P>
<P>
Ministers of the three states will meet together at the EAC
headquarters in Arusha, northern Tanzania, from Monday to
Wednesday to discuss and approve the new strategy, the U.N.
Center for Human Settlements (Habitat) based here said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The strategy, known as the East African Community Development
Program, will tackle various challenges in human settlements
development in east Africa through participatory and
collaborative efforts at regional, national and community levels.
</P>
<P>
It will focus on encouraging people's direct involvement in
improving their living conditions and enlarging the capacities of
the local, national and regional institutions that serve them.
</P>
<P>
The strategy will also seek to gain more access to appropriate
technology in human settlements development, harmonizing relevant
policies of the three states and promoting their strategic
partnerships, effective coordination and collaboration in the
field.
</P>
<P>
The living standards, particularly of the poor segments of the
population in most parts of east Africa, have continued to
decline steadily in recent years, the Habitat claimed in a press
release.
</P>
<P>
While many rural residents live in temporary structures made
of mud, poles, and thatch, conditions are worse in the urban
areas, where millions live in overcrowded informal settlements
that lack basic services such as safe drinking water, sanitation
and health care, the agency lamented.
</P>
<P>
Around 60 delegates from the EAC member countries are also
expected to attend the Arusha meeting to seek agreements on the
strategic areas of cooperation and to reconfirm their countries'
commitment to the implementation of the Habitat Agenda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Curb of Repeated Construction Urgent Task </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 19 (Xinhua) -- The People's Daily, the
country's leading newspaper, said today that duplicate
construction needs to be stopped.
</P>
<P>
Construction needs to meet market demand, and excessive
construction will hinder quality and efficiency, a commentary of
the paper said, and that one gauge of rational construction is
supply and demand and another is utilization of capacity, with 80
percent or higher utilization being considered reasonable.
</P>
<P>
In China, the supply and demand of farm products, energy, raw
materials, and infrastructure are basically balanced, while there
is a surplus of many processed products like machinery,
electronics, and textiles, and a shortage of of better processed
products, it said.
</P>
<P>
In analyzing the reasons for the overlapping of construction, the
commentary said that some construction is actually the result of
market demand. This kind of construction can improve competitive
ability and meet consumer demand, but it may also run into
financial difficulties and cause enterprises to fail. The consumer
electronics goods surplus is one example.
</P>
<P>
Another kind of repetition is production based on outdated
polices that fail to follow the changing market situation. The
glut of textiles is an example.
</P>
<P>
Another problem is that industries blindly seek to expand,
resulting in low-grade repetition. This problem can be found in
some machine manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
Lack of mature reforms and relevant legislation is also to be
blamed. This has caused over-heated development of commerce,
foreign trade, finance and real estate.
</P>
<P>
The commentary said that repetition in future can be stopped by
abiding by the rules of the socialist market economy and
tightening macro-economic regulation and controls. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Support Packaging Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 19 (Xinhua) -- China plans to invest ten
billion yuan in 1996-2000 to support the development of packaging
industry.
</P>
<P>
Large and medium-sized packaging firms will be the major
beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
Though the country's packaging industry maintained an average
of 29 percent growth rate in the past few year, 80 percent of its
products are of poor-quality, noted specialists.
</P>
<P>
So far, the country has more than 4,000 such firms, employing
500,000 people and producing 3,000 varieties of products. But the
country still suffers 14 billion yuan of loss a year because of poor
equipment and technology in 20 percent of the firms.
</P>
<P>
China's per capita consumption of packaging materials stands at
20 kg while that in some developed countrys at 210 kg, noted
specialists.
</P>
<P>
According to a national economic plan, the country will provide
100 billion yuan to 200 billion yuan-worth equipment for food
processing and packaging industry in the next few years, which will
offer great opportunities for packaging firms.
</P>
<P>
Specialists also suggested the industry pays more attention to
develop low-cost and high-efficient packaging and recycling of
waste packages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
