<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plan to Be Drafted to Ban Export of Hazardous </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Ministers from various
governments are to work out a worldwide export ban next week of
hazardous wastes from developed countries to developing ones, the
Nairobi-based U.N. Environmental Program (UNEP) said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Meeting next Monday in Kuching, Malaysia, under the auspices
of the Basel Convention, governmental ministers will decide what
kind of wastes to be banned internationally, said UNEP Executive
Director Klaus Topfer.
</P>
<P>
Two lists of wastes developed by the Basel Convention's
Technical Working Group will be presented at the one-week
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The first "hazardous waste" list would ban the export of
wastes containing arsenic, lead, mercury, asbestos, and dozens of
other chemicals and substances.
</P>
<P>
The second "non-hazardous" list includes wastes that can be
safely recycled or re-used and will normally not be covered by
the ban treaty. This includes scrap iron, steel or copper,
certain electronic assemblies, non-hazardous chemical catalysts,
and many ceramics, solid plastics and paper and textile wastes.
</P>
<P>
"The adoption of these lists will help clarify the rules of
the game and enable governments to satisfy both environmental and
economic concerns," said Topfer.
</P>
<P>
"Such global environmental cooperation is critical at this
time in which we witness the globalization of the economy, of
markets, and of products," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Clearly specifying which wastes are covered by the
Convention, and which are not, will enable countries to make more
informed economic decisions," noted the U.N. official.
</P>
<P>
Annually the Earth sees a production of 400 million tons of
wastes hazardous to people or the environment because they are
toxic, poisonous, explosive, corrosive, flammable, or infectious.
</P>
<P>
The Basel Convention on the Control of Trans-boundary
Movements of Hazardous Wastes and Their Disposal was adopted in
March 1989 after a series of notorious "toxic cargoes" from
industrialized nations were dumped in developing and eastern
European countries.
</P>
<P>
The convention, taking effect in May 1992, strictly regulates
the trans-boundary movements of such wastes and provides
obligations to its members to ensure that such wastes are managed
and disposed of in an environmentally sound manner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brunei Supports Use of Regional Currencies in Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Brunei has agreed to the
proposal to use regional currencies in trade among ASEAN member
countries, Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said Brunei's Sultan Hassanal Bolkiah agreed to the
proposal during a meeting with him in Bandar Seri Begawan, capital
of Brunei, Wednesday.
</P>
