the Philippines, Singapore and Indonesia and we made a general
assessment of the economic situation and the type of cooperation
we proposed among ASEAN countries," Mahathir, who returned from
Brunei to Sabah, east Malaysia earlier Thursday, told at a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
On the region's protracted currency depreciation problem,
Mahathir said ASEAN (the Association of Southeast Asian Nations)
is now under pressure.
</P>
<P>
"Because of the pressure from outside, it's difficult for us.
If left to ourselves, we can manage our economy but every time we
do something, they apply pressure," Mahathir was quoted as saying
by the Malaysian national news agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
On international concern over Indonesia's proposal for a
currency board system, Mahathir said: "Maybe they are concerned
but the concern is made worse by opinions which will only cause
the rupiah to go down."
</P>
<P>
"We feel that Indonesia is an independent country. They
(Indonesia) have accepted all the conditions (of the International
Monetary Fund) already. Some things must be left for them to
decide but if everything is being forced and if it is successful,
it's alright but if not successful, the so-called 'help' has not
helped Indonesia at all," he said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is reportedly considering adopting a currency board
system that pegs the rupiah to the U.S. dollar at a fixed rate to
help pull the country out of its current economic slump. But the
IMF opposed such a system and warned that the 40-billion-dollars
bailout it had extended to the country could be in jeopardy if the
Indonesian government went ahead with the scheme.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sees Improvement in Quality of Engineering Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 19 (Xinhua) -- China has achieved much in
improving the quality of various engineering and housing projects,
thanks to the effective supervision and monitoring system
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Vice-minister of construction Tan Qinglian told Xinhua today
that large groups of China's key projects and large urban public
facilities as well as nearly one billion sq m of newly-built
housing projects have been up to the advanced world standard or
have met the State targets in terms of construction quality.
</P>
<P>
A national survey on construction quality shows that the
qualification rate of the country's engineering and housing
projects has increased by 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, breakthroughs have been made in planning, designing
and construction of the country's engineering and housing projects
and big headway was made in protecting environment and in
completing the infrastructural facilities.
</P>
<P>
According to the senior official, more than 90 percent of
China's cities and counties have set up engineering quality
supervision stations, which cover 88 percent of the country's
construction projects.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the country has practised the engineering
monitoring system, establishing a total of 1,500 construction
monitoring institutes, which handled or prevented some 60,000
hidden construction hazards and troubles in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Despite the progress, many loopholes still exist, particularly
in the construction of residential housing, the vice-minister
said, adding that much still needs to be done in this respect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
