<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saddam Receives Message From Yeltsin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
Thursday received a written message from Russian President Boris
Yeltsin on the Iraq crisis.
</P>
<P>
The message also dealt with the visit by U.N. Secretary General
Kofi Annan scheduled for Friday, Iraq News Agency reported. But no
further details of the message were available
</P>
<P>
The message was handed over by Russian Deputy Foreign Minister
Viktor Posuvalyuk, also Yeltsin's special envoy.
</P>
<P>
The news agency added that Saddam expressed appreciation of
Russia's efforts for reaching a political solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The United States threatened to launch military attack on Iraq
if it does not allow U.N. weapons inspectors free entry to
sensitive sites. Baghdad has barred them from places like
presidential sites, citing national sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Saddam was quoted as affirming that Iraq will make all efforts
to make Annan's upcoming visit a success and spare the region the
dangers of a war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
