<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Banks to Open Branches in South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, February 19 (Xinhua) -- South Korea has approved plans
for four foreign banks to open or upgrade their offices to
branches here this year, a spokesman for the Office of Bank
Supervision said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The four banking institutions are Morgan Guaranty Trust of New
York, State Street Bank and Trust Co. of the United States, Lehman
Brothers Bank of Germany, and Union Bank of Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Morgan Guaranty and Lehman Brothers are planning to upgrade
their offices in the capital to branch banks in the first half of
this year.
</P>
<P>
Union Bank has decided to close its securities branch and open
a new branch bank here this year.
</P>
<P>
State Street Bank will set up a branch office in Seoul for
liaison and economic data activities.
</P>
<P>
U.S. credit-rating company Standard &AMP; Poor recently gave a
triple-A rating to Morgan Guaranty, an A+ rating to Lehman
Brothers, and a double A+ to Union Bank of Switzerland, while
State Street received a double A credit rating from Fitch IBCA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
