<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drug Abuse, Trafficking Continue to Rise in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Drug abuse and trafficking
continue to rise in Africa in an alleged climate of "tolerance,"
the U.N. International Narcotics Control Board (INCB) said here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Despite eradication efforts and significant seizures in some
African states, the continent remains a major supplier of
cannabis and cannabis resin to rapidly-growing domestic illicit
markets, as well as to Europe and North America, INCB said.
</P>
<P>
Some African seaports and airports have become major transit
centers for cocaine from South America destined for Europe, and
for heroin from Asia to Europe and North America, the INCB noted
in its annual report which is to be officially published next
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
There is an apparent increase in tolerance of the illicit drug
culture across Africa, as in recent years, drug use and abuse in
certain circles has gained acceptability, it noted.
</P>
<P>
Once again, drug abuse, appears to be almost normal, even
fashionable in Africa, especially in the big cities, said the
agency, giving evidents in the pop music, fashion, entertainment
industries, media and many other areas in society.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
