<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Degrading Freshwater Resources May Spark "Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 19 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Environment Program
(UNEP) warned Thursday that deteriorating freshwater shortages
around the world may cause "water wars" if there is a lack of
strong national policies and global cooperation countering
against the trend.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the body announced that environment ministers and
high-level officials from around the world have been summoned to
attend a meeting at its headquarters here in the Kenyan capital
from March 2 to 4 to discuss, among others, the issue of
freshwater shortages.
</P>
<P>
"The potential for conflict or `water wars' is great, and this
issue needs urgent political attention," UNEP chief Klaus Topfer
noted, adding that "in some cases, competition for water may lead
to conflicts over trans-boundary resources."
</P>
<P>
This is partly because there are few international agreements
to provide for the sustainable management and use of water
resources contained in about 300 shared international river
basins around the world, he explained.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said, "it is estimated that 25,000 people die
each day as a result of poor water quality. Indeed, waterborne
diseases still represent the single largest cause of human
sickness and death worldwide."
</P>
<P>
Some 1.7 billion people, more than one-third of the world's
total population, are without safe water supply and an estimated
one-quarter of the Earth will suffer from chronic water shortages
at the beginning of the next century.
</P>
<P>
"The proportion of people without access to adequate supplies
of clean, safe freshwater is greater in Africa than anywhere else
in the world", said Topfer. Africa has 19 out of the 25 states in
the world which have the highest percentage of populations
without access to safe drinking water.
</P>
<P>
Global priorities on the issue should be put on the more
effective use of water, the equitable distribution of water among
countries that share international river-basins, the prevention
from water pollution and the impact of major dams and diversion
projects, he urged.
</P>
<P>
An adequate supply of safe, clean water is the most important
precondition for sustaining human life, for maintaining
ecosystems that support all life, and for achieving sustainable
development, he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0141 </DOCNO>
