<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Remember Two Great Leaders (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 19 (Xinhua) -- China has been holding
various activities to commemorate its two great leaders, Zhou
Enlai and Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
This year is the 100th birth anniversary of Zhou Enlai, the
first premier of the People's Republic of China. When he died 22
years ago, Beijing's Chang'an Avenue and Tian'anmen Square were a
sea of tears.
</P>
<P>
This month, both the Chinese capital and Zhou's native province
of Jiangsu are holding seminars and photo exhibitions in his
honor. Beijing TV is also running a series, "Zhou Enlai in the
past 100 Years". According to a newspaper survey, the main reason
the people of Beijing are interested in the series is that they
esteem him.
</P>
<P>
The survey in Beijing shows that what impressed audiences most
was Zhou's care for the common people, and 72 percent of the
people questioned said that tears came to their eyes when they
watched the program.
</P>
<P>
Next month, the series will be shown on China Central
Television Station during prime time.
</P>
<P>
Today is the first anniversary of the death of Deng Xiaoping,
who was regarded as the "chief architect of China's reforms and
opening-up". People attended various commemorative activities,
even in the early morning sleet, to show their respect for him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Orders Ban on Sending Workers to Middle East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 19 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
ordered a temporary ban on sending Filipino overseas workers to
the Middle East in anticipation of a possible outbreak of armed
hostilities in the Gulf area.
</P>
<P>
Tension in the Middle East could adversely affect some 600,000
Filipino workers there who would be displaced as many of them had
been during the 1991 Gulf War, the Philippine News Agency said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government has placed on "full alert" all its
embassies and consular offices in the Gulf area which are prepared
to evacuate Filipino workers in danger zones should fighting break
out.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Affairs Undersecretary Leonides Caday said Thursday
that other agencies are also under orders for immediate
mobilization in case evacuation become necessary.
</P>
<P>
Caday said they had raised alert level one in the Gulf with
team leaders who have been designated to implement systematic
evacuation when ordered. The alert, he said, comes in four levels
with Level four representing actual evacuation.
</P>
<P>
Emergency evacuation of Filipinos in danger zones will consist
primarily of airlifting them to safer grounds in the neighboring
Middle East countries by the Philippine Air Force, which did the
same thing in 1991, he said. 
</P>
