<HEADLINE> Share Prices Continue to Rise on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Share prices continued to
rise on the Singapore market as the benchmark Straits Times
Industrials Index (STII) increased by 14.49 points to close at
1,553.47 points on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that stock prices finished broadly firmer though
most bank stocks ended in negative territory. They said investors
were trying to absorb news that bank earnings would be down by 30
percent in 1997 as a result of higher provisions for regional
exposure.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume increased to 582.53 million units,
valued at 654.41 million Singapore dollars (about 399.03 million
US dollars). Advances continued to lead declines by 295 to 102,
while 214 other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Renong Bhd was the most actively traded counter as it
registered a turnover of 61.94 million units. It was followed by
M. Resources which had 34.3 million shares traded. RHB Capital
Warrant99 was next with 32.98 million units changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Transmarco and Venture Warrant9907 shared the top spot on the
gainers' list as each of them rose by 70 cents to finish at 10.5
and 4.7 Singapore dollars respectively. Asean Fund increased by 50
cents to end at 8.5 Singapore dollars. City Developments was up by
40 cents to close at 6.8 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, DBS (Development Bank of Singapore) Foreign
was the biggest loser as it declined by 60 cents to end at 12.4
Singapore dollars. OUB (Overseas Union Bank) Foreign fell by 25
cents to close at 5.65 Singapore dollars, while City Developments
Warrant98 lost 24 cents to finish at 4.16 Singapore dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
