<HEADLINE> GM Component Supplier Signs Climate Control Venture in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 19 (Xinhua) -- China's largest automotive air
conditioning maker based in Shanghai recently signed a joint
venture agreement with Delphi Automotive Systems to manufacture
air conditioner components for the Chinese automotive market.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Delphi Automovie Air Conditioning Systems
Co. Ltd. will partner the Shanghai Automotive Air Conditioner
Factory (SAAC) and Delphi Harrison Thermal System, the parts and
components business of General Motors Corp.
</P>
<P>
The new company will make air condition modules and heat
exchangers, including condensers, evaporators and heater
cores. Financial terms are not being released.
</P>
<P>
This is Delphi Thermal's first operation in China. SAAC
controls 66 percent of the joint venture, with Delphi holding the
remaining 34 percent, according to Delphi President
J.T. Battenberg.
</P>
<P>
The venture, to be located in the Pudong New Area of Shanghai,
expects to start operation later this month, and will have an
annual production capacity of 400,000 units.
</P>
<P>
As part of the joint venture, a new structure will be built to
manufacture products for Shanghai General Motors, a GM mid-sized
car-making joint venture, beginning in the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The new venture "allows for us to provide components for both
current and future Chinese vehicle manufacturer," said Battenberg.
</P>
<P>
SAAC now occupies 70 percent of the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
Delphi Automotive Systems now has 11 joint ventures and four
wholly owned facilities in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
