<HEADLINE> Egypt Expresses Reservation over Outcome of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's permanent representative
to the United Nations Nabil el Arabi Thursday expressed his
reservation over the outcome of U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan's upcoming visit to Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East News Agency (MENA) quoted the official as
saying that progress was made regarding the proposed weapons
inspection formula for Iraqi suspected sites Annan would take with
him to Iraq on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has accepted that Annan would appoint political
observers in the U.N. weapons inspection teams, he said.
</P>
<P>
"However, no one can fully guarantee the success or the failure
of Annan's visit," Arabi added.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian diplomat said he has spoken to Annan, who himself
"does not know whether his mission would succeed or fail."
</P>
<P>
Annan, with the backing of the five permanent members of the
U.N. Security Council, leaves New York for Paris on Thursday and
will arrive in Baghdad on Friday, the MENA said.
</P>
<P>
"It (the visit) will be a very short one. I expect Annan to
return to New York by Monday or Tuesday," Arabi said, "because
obviously the U.S. has taken all necessary measures."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief's trip to Baghdad is widely believed as the last
chance to solve the Iraq-U.N. crisis peacefully.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain have threatened to launch military strike
on Iraq if diplomacy fails to end the current standoff between
Iraq and the U.N. over weapons inspection.  
</P>
</TEXT>
