<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Young Scholars Win Social Sciences Awards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 19 (Xinhua) -- China today granted awards to
young scholars who have made outstanding achievements in social
science research.
</P>
<P>
A total of 99 books and theses won Hu Shen Awards and
the National Awards for Outstanding Achievements, the most famous
awards for young social science scholars in the country.
</P>
<P>
Most prizes went to pragmatic research topics, particularly
economics and sociology, which are very helpful to the country's
moderization drive.
</P>
<P>
They deal with subjects like finance, the reform of
state-enterprises, rural labor, the Hong Kong issue, a market
economy, laws and foreign situations.
</P>
<P>
Such a trend in the academic community shows that social
sciences are becoming an engine pushing the reform and opening up
as natural sciences, observers say.
</P>
<P>
Some awards also went to the research into the origin of Chinese
civilization, the study of the culture of bamboo, and the study of
Confucius.
</P>
<P>
The study of Deng Xiaoping Theory also received a prize,
according to the sponsors at the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Li Ruihuan, member of the Standing Committee of the Political
Bureau of the Chinese Communist Party Central Committee, sent a
letter of congratulations to the award ceremony to congratulate
the winners. Head of the Publicity Department of the CPC Central
Committee Ding Guangen and State Councilor Li Tieying also sent
letters of congratulations to the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Giving awards to young scholars is regarded as a move to
encourage more talented people to do research work, as the country
is facing a shortage of scholars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
