<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Bank Earnings Expected to Decline in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's six major banks
are expected to see their earnings in the aggregate decline by
about 30 percent in 1997 as a result of exceptional provisions for
regional risk, Deputy Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong said on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Asked to give the latest update on loans extended by local and
foreign financial institutions to regional economies, especially
Indonesia, Lee told parliament that as of December 31, 1997, the
six local banking groups had loans and investments amounting to
37.2 billion Singapore dollars (22.68 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The sum accounted for 16 percent of their total assets in
Malaysia, Indonesia, Thailand, South Korea and the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
"Two-thirds of this exposure was in Malaysia, where Singapore
banks have long established operations. Their exposure to
Indonesia was 5.4 billion Singapore dollars (3.29 billion
dollars), or 2.3 percent of their total assets," said the deputy
prime minister, who is now also head of the Monetary Authority of
Singapore (MAS), the de facto central bank.
</P>
<P>
The six major banks are the United Overseas Bank (UOB),
Overseas Union Bank (OUB), the Development Bank of Singapore
(DBS), the Overseas Chinese Banking Corporation (OCBC), the Keppel
Bank, and the Tat Lee Bank. The last two had announced their
merger in January this year.
</P>
<P>
Lee said the total classified loans of the six local banking
groups to these five countries accounted for 5.7 percent of their
loans to these countries.
</P>
<P>
The total classified loans of the local banks, including both
local and overseas loans, were 2.6 percent of their total loan
portfolios. As a percentage of their total global assets, this was
2.3 percent. "These figures remain well within comfortable
limits," he said.
</P>
<P>
"All six banks are financially sound. They have strong capital
positions, exceeding 12 percent of their risk-weighted assets,
higher than most banks in other countries. They also sit on
substantial reserves," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
