<HEADLINE> Portugal to Set up Joint Army with African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Defense ministers from
Portugal and five Portuguese-speaking African countries will meet
in Lisbon, Portugal, in July to discuss the launching of a joint
army.
</P>
<P>
According to a report Thursday by the Angola News Agency, the
prime mission of the joint army is to carry out peace-keeping
operations in Africa under the resolutions by the United Nations
and the Organization of African Unity, to ensure peace and
stability on the African continent and in Portuguese-speaking
African countries.
</P>
<P>
Another purpose for the establishment of the joint army is to
enhance cooperation between Portugal and the five African
countries, namely Angola, Mozambique, Guinea Bissau, Cape Verde
and San Tome &AMP; Principe.
</P>
<P>
At present, Portugal has sustained cooperation in military
technology with the five countries, training young officers in
its military academies for the African countries.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Brazilian Ambassador to Portugal will also
attend the defense ministers' meeting in the capacity of observer
so as to demonstrate the importance of joint action in the
international arena. 
</P>
</TEXT>
