<HEADLINE> Repolling Starts in Six Indian States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Repolling started Thursday
in six Indian states following complaints about irregularities in
the first phase of the 12th Lower House of Parliament elections on
February 16.
</P>
<P>
Repolling was held at 288 polling stations in Bihar State and
191 in Uttar Pradesh Thursday. More complaints about
irregularities have been reported in the two states.
</P>
<P>
Thursday also witnessed repolling at specified polling stations
in other states such as Manipur, Karnataka, Rajasthan and Andhra
Pradesh.
</P>
<P>
The Election Commission has ordered repolling at 821 polling
stations covering 44 parliamentary constituencies in Bihar and
Uttar Pradesh on grounds of booth capturing and electoral
malpractice. Repolling in both Bihar and Uttar Pradesh had been
reportedly peaceful.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of polling held on Monday, one of the four
phases of the 12th Lower House of Parliament elections, was to
elect 222 members of 543 MPs in parts of the country including New
Delhi, capital of the country. According to the election schedule
made by the Election Commission, the other three phases of
elections would be held on February 22 and 28 and March 7.
</P>
<P>
This is the second general election in less than two years.
India held its general election in April-May 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
