<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Papers Applaud SAR's First Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 19 (Xinhua) -- All major Hong Kong
newspapers Thursday expressed support to the Special
Administrative Region (SAR)'s first Budget, which was unveiled
Wednesday by Financial Secretary Donald Tsang.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong Commercial Daily commented that the first Financial
Budget drawn up independently by the SAR, when unfolded yesterday,
gained positive reaction from all walks of life, different parties
and the media community. The Chinese daily said that this is "a
Budget to boost people's confidence", which proposed targeted
measures to relieve the burdens on people and to improve Hong
Kong's economy.
</P>
<P>
Express News said in its editorial that the Budget did a good
job in restoring confidence in Hong Kong's economy. The Financial
Secretary predicted an exceptionally high level of fiscal surplus
totaling 77 billion HK dollars (9.9 billion U.S. dollars) for
1997-98, demonstrating the SAR's resolve and strength to maintain
the linked exchange rate, said the Chinese paper.
</P>
<P>
Wen Wei Po said that the Budget reflected Hong Kong people's
wisdom for governing Hong Kong and the administration's vision in
pursuing sustained, long-term economic growth. The Budget also is
also designed to give relief to the people in the time of
economic uncertainty, and reduce tax burdens on businesses. "It is
a pragmatic and far-sighted Budget," said the Chinese paper.
</P>
<P>
Ta Kung Pao's commentary said that the SAR's first Budget is
widely welcomed, Ming Pao said that "it is a good Budget and
deserves support", and Hong Kong Daily News said "it is a Budget
well received by taxpayers, especially the middle class".
</P>
<P>
South China Morning Post said in its editorial Thursday that
the Budget was a well balanced one. The English paper said, "in
times of turbulence, such solid reserves help to underline the
distinction between free-market Hong Kong and the economies in
trouble elsewhere in Asia."
</P>
<P>
Another English daily Hong Kong Standard carried a front-paged
editorial, saying that the budget has gladdened many a
middle-income heart with lower taxes, lower rates and mortgage
relief. Noting that the tax cuts proposed by the Financial
Secretary will benefit 99 percent of taxpayers, the paper
commented: "That's something no financial secretary in the rest of
 Asia can afford to do this year, perhaps not even in the next."
The paper concluded that a positive, well-received Budget would
have a strong psychological impact. 
</P>
</TEXT>
