<HEADLINE> UN Chief's Advance Team Arrives in Baghdad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, February 19 (Xinhua) -- A U.N. advance team in
preparation for U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's upcoming visit
to Iraq arrived at the Habbaniya airport in Baghdad Thursday noon.
</P>
<P>
The team is composed of about 20 staff. They said at the
airport that they are here to prepare for Annan's scheduled visit
to Baghdad this weekend.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief announced on Tuesday that he will make a trip to
Baghdad Friday to try to find a diplomatic solution to the crisis
over the U.N. weapons inspection in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He said that he would hold meetings directly with Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Annan's upcoming visit to Baghdad was seen as the "last ditch"
international effort to resolve the current crisis peacefully.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain have threatened to launch military strike
on Iraq if diplomacy fails to make Baghdad comply with
U.N. Security Council resolutions and pry open its sites suspected
of hiding banned weapons.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz has voiced welcome to
Annan's visit to Iraq, saying he is ready to receive Annan and
discuss with him the issue of the search of Iraqi presidential
sites in order to solve the crisis "created by the United States."
</P>
<P>
Iraq has said that it would try to make a success Annan's
mediation mission in Iraq to settle the current crisis peacefully.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the three-men U.N. technical team sent
by Annan last Sunday to survey the eight Iraqi presidential
palaces ended its work Wednesday evening, Iraqi newspaper
Al-Thawra reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The team, which includes two Austrian weapons experts, is going
to submit a report to Annan during the latter's visit to Baghdad.


19/02/98 12:10 GMT

NNNN
20:12 20:12 g # PAB
