<HEADLINE> HK Business Community Welcomes First SAR Budget (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Leaders and organizations
from such sectors as industry, finance, trade, tourism and
service in Hong Kong welcomed the Budget speech delivered by
Financial Secretary Donald Tsang Yam-kuen here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Henry Tang, chairman of the Federation of Hong Kong Industries,
described the Budget, the first of its kind since the Special
Administrative Region was established last July, as "a good and
balanced" one which demonstrated continuing prudent financial
management.
</P>
<P>
"We are happy that our calls for a reduction in profits tax
have been heeded," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also welcomed the proposal to allow an immediate 100 percent
write-off for new expenditure on plant and machinery specifically
related to manufacturing and computer hardware and software.
</P>
<P>
"This will help strengthen Hong Kong's position as a commercial
center," he stated.
</P>
<P>
The Stock Exchange of Hong Kong gave a good response to the
government's decision to reduce stamp duty on stock transactions.
</P>
<P>
It expressed the belief that this is a step in the right
direction and hoped that stamp duty will be abolished eventually
as the tax constitutes a major part of the transaction cost of
stock trading in Hong Kong and affects the competitiveness of the
market.
</P>
<P>
Anthony Neoh, chairman of the Securities and Futures Commission
(SFC), said he was pleased with the positive messages in the
speech and pledged that the SFC will work with the government in
reviewing the regulatory system in the wake of recent market
volatility.
</P>
<P>
He said the reduction in stamp duty on stock transactions from
0.3 percent to 0.25 percent would further enhance the
competitiveness of the Hong Kong securities market.
</P>
