<HEADLINE> Container Transport Tonnage up 31 Percent over 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 19 (Xinhua) -- China handled 10.77 million
TEUs (Twenty-foot Equivalent Units) in 1997, up 31 percent over
the previous year, according to statistics released today by the
Ministry of Communications.
</P>
<P>
The statistics also show that the country's container transport
industry has grown at an average annual rate in excess of 20
percent for 13 consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
China now has more than 100 large container terminals with an
annual handling capacity of approximately 80 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, the country's largest business center, ranked first
in the country in transporting containers. Shenzhen, a special
economic zone in south China, came in second. And Qingdao, a port
city in east China's Shandong Province ranked third.
</P>
<P>
The rest of the top 10, in order, were the port cities of
Tianjin, Guangzhou, Xiamen, Dalian, Zhuhai, Ningbo and Fuzhou,
according to an official from the Ministry of Communications.
</P>
<P>
The rapid development of China's container transport industry
has increased the country's foreign trade and the industry was
expected to be an economic growth area, the official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
