<HEADLINE> AL Chief Hails Annan's Visit as New Hope for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 19 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary General
Kofi Annan's scheduled visit to Baghdad Friday revives "all hopes"
for averting a military confrontation, Arab League chief Esmat
Abdel-Meguid said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The Arab League fully supports the implementation of
U.N. resolutions, a peaceful settlement to the Iraqi crisis and
the prevention of force that will be a real regional disaster,"
he was quoted by the Middle East News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
The AL chief, who met with Iraqi President Saddam Hussein in
Baghdad recently in a bid to soften the Iraqi stance, said the
Iraqi leader was in fact seeking a diplomatic solution to the
standoff with the United States over U.N. arms inspection.
</P>
<P>
"He should receive all the help and support to reach a peaceful
settlement and avert a military confrontation," Abdel-Meguid
added.
</P>
<P>
He said that the situation now is totally different from the
circumstances that evoked the Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led multinational forces drove Iraq out from its
neighboring state Kuwait in 1991. The Iraqis have since been
living under U.N.-imposed sanctions and succumbed to seven years
of U.N. arms inspection.
</P>
<P>
The recent crisis between the U.N. and Iraq was ignited in
November over Baghdad's refusal to let the U.N. Special Commission
(UNSCOM) in charge of scrapping Iraqi weapons of mass destruction
into its presidential sites.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has completed an extensive naval, air and troops
buildup in the Gulf in preparation for a strike if Baghdad
continues to bar "presidential sites" to U.N. arms inspectors, a
central dispute of the current crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
