<HEADLINE> Inland Water Transport Development Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Zou
Jiahua today urged efforts to tap the potential of inland river
navigation in a bid to improve the country's transportation
services.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a national meeting on inland water transport
construction that ended here today, Zou said inland water
transport is inexpensive and energy-efficient, and causes less
pollution, compared to other transport means.
</P>
<P>
He said China enjoys advantages in developing inland water
transport as it has many rivers suitable for
navigation. "It is an indispensable part of the national transport
network and making better use of it will certainly help ease the
country's transport congestions."
</P>
<P>
The leader outlined strategies for developing inland
river transport, such as improving planning while
giving priority to major projects, gradually standardizing ships
and shipping operations, raising funds from all channels for
navigation development and updating ship-building
technology. 
