<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Budget Suggests HK Maintains Simple, Low Tax Regime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 19 (Xinhua) -- The largest-ever package of
tax concessions unveiled Wednesday in Hong Kong's 1998-1999 budget
sends a clear message that Hong Kong tries to maintain "a simple,
certain and competitive tax system" which appeals to investors, a
major tax services firm said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Moderate tax cuts and incentives offered by the first Special
Administrative Region (SAR), combined with the curbing of the
threat of double taxation, show that "one country, two tax
systems" is being honestly implemented in Hong Kong, said Joseph
Wang, tax partner of Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu.
</P>
<P>
The budget, coming out at a time of economic uncertainty,
focused on two key issues: maintaining economic growth and
ensuring stability and confidence, he told a budget seminar hosted
by the firm.
</P>
<P>
He hailed the budget as "scoring very well, sprinkling salt and
pepper evenly at the main dish."
</P>
<P>
Another tax partner of the firm, Sarah McGrath, commented that
"everyone was asking for a lot, but not expecting much" from the
budget, but "now we have more than we anticipated."
</P>
<P>
The package of tax measures, costing the revenue 13.6 billion
HK dollars (1.7 billion U.S. dollars) in the financial year
starting April 1998, has positive effects on promoting Hong Kong
as a financial, service and trade center, McGrath noted.
</P>
<P>
The budget proposed, among others, a reduction of corporate
profits tax from 16.5 to 16 percent, the lowest level in the
region, immediate write-off for expenditure on manufacturing plant
 and machinery and computer hardware and software, reduction of
stamp duty levied on stock trading from 0.3 to 0.25 percent and
cuts in hotel accommodation tax and air passenger departure tax to
 help revive tourism.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the financial secretary's statement in the budget
that Hong Kong has reached an understanding with its biggest
trading partner, the Chinese mainland, for avoidance of double
taxation, McGrath said: "This will further boost cross-the-border
business."
</P>
<P>
Henry Tang Ying-yan, member of the SAR Executive Council and
chairman of the Federation of Hong Kong Industries, also addressed
the seminar.
</P>
<P>
He said he, like everyone else, is "generally pleased with and
fully supports" the budget, which has taken into account many
views from various sectors of the community and tried to create a
business-friendly environment.
</P>
<P>
The budget offered some relief to the industrial and commercial
sector which faces a tougher year in 1998, Tang said.
</P>
<P>
But it still can do better in boosting the manufacturing sector
and helping small and medium-sized enterprises which form the
backbone of Hong Kong's economy, the industrialist noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
