<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Economy on Sound Track </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 19 (Xinhua) -- A State Statistical Bureau
(SSB) report issued today shows that China maintained stable
national economic growth during January, with industrial
enterprises generating value-added of 137.8 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The daily industrial value-added grew by 11.3 percent on the
1997 period, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The state-owned sector registered 5.2 percent growth in
value-added during January, with the figure for collective
enterprises growing by 13 percent on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
The value-added for nation's light industrial sector grew by
12.5 percent to 63 billion yuan, with the figure for heavy
industry ending at 74.8 billion yuan, up 10.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The January retail sales volume hit 255 billion yuan, up 14.6
percent when considering the inflation rate. Retail sales in urban
areas grew by 15 percent to 157.2 billion yuan, with the 97.8
billion yuan figure for rural areas representing growth of 14
percent.
</P>
<P>
The January foreign trade volume stood at 21.4 billion US
dollars, down 1.2 percent on an annual basis. The export volume
reached 12.7 billion dollars, up 8.8 percent, with imports falling
by 12.9 percent to end at 8.7 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
January consumer prices fell slightly by 0.3 percent on the
1997 period, with retail prices dropping by 1.5 percent, according
to the SSB report.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
