<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Minister Calls New Regulation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan Media Minister
Mangala Samaraweera said Thursday that a new publication
regulation issued two days ago is aimed at protecting children
from being exposed to violent pictures.
</P>
<P>
Under the regulation, publication of any photographs depicting
a person killed or injured as a result of a bomb explosion or any
other acts, or any part of the body of any such person, will be
prohibited.
</P>
<P>
The new regulation, called the Emergency Regulation of
Photographs, was issued by President Chandrika Kumaratunga on
Tuesday in accordance with the Public Security Ordinance of Sri
Lanka.
</P>
<P>
Any person who violates the provisions of the regulation will
be guilty of an offense, it says.
</P>
<P>
Samaraweera told a news conference that the publication of such
kind of pictures has become part of the people's daily life during
the past one and half decades.
</P>
<P>
This kind of publications have very bad effects on young
children, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Apparently, exposure to such pictures in the long term could
create "a very violent generation in the future, even more violent
than they are now," he claimed.
</P>
<P>
There have been many complaints about the publication of such
photos. As a result, the president issued the regulation in order
to control the publication, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
In many Sri Lankan newspapers or on other electronic media,
pictures of dead bodies or body parts were often highlighted after
a bomb explosion or similar attacks occurred.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
