<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Education, Careers Exposition Opens in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 19 (Xinhua) -- An education and careers
exposition opened here Thursday to provide advice on education
and career opportunities to Hong Kong's students and job seekers.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 exhibitors will present the latest information on
education and careers opportunities to students and the working
public during the exposition, which will last until February 22 at
the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Center.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony, Michael Sze, executive
director of the Hong Kong Trade Development Council, one of the
organizers of the exposition, said the show is important because
it is right at the heart of the future of Hong Kong and its
students.
</P>
<P>
"It is important to prepare our youth for the rapidly changing
world and that they can master the skill and knowledge and
dedicate themselves to building a better Hong Kong," Sze said.
</P>
<P>
Among the exhibitors are 133 educational institutes
representing Hong Kong, China's mainland, Australia, the United
States, the United Kingdom, New Zealand, Switzerland, Canada,
Germany and India.
</P>
<P>
They offer a wide range of learning opportunities covering
undergraduate and postgraduate programs, distance learning
courses, language and adult education courses and vocational
training.
</P>
<P>
Following last year's success, the State Education Commission
of China has organized a delegation of 33 prestigious higher
education institutes, offering local students direct access to
academic training in the mainland.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony, Provisional Legislative Council member
Tam Yiu-chung encouraged Hong Kong's young people to pursue
further education abroad and serve Hong Kong better when they come
back.
</P>
<P>
Tam said Hong Kong, an international city and financial center,
is now providing services to the global market.
</P>
<P>
If one has overseas experience and expertise, he or she will
definitely be in a competitive position, Tam said.
</P>
<P>
Commissioner for Labor Jacqueline Willis said the exposition
will offer a comprehensive overview of the most up-to-date
careers, training and education opportunities available.
</P>
<P>
In the career section, 69 exhibitors from local private
enterprises, government departments, public bodies and
professional associations feature career opportunities in areas of
insurance, finance, personnel consultancy, legal practice,
accounting, social service, engineering, mass media, tourism and
property services.
</P>
<P>
The exposition would provide a forum where young people could
gain a better understanding of the labor market by having
face-to-face contact with experienced professionals from various
fields and by attending seminars and video shows on different
industries.
</P>
<P>
For those who want help in choosing the right career path, the
Labor Department's Careers Advisory Service helps individuals make
informed decisions.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the different booths and exhibits, 60 seminars
on education and career options and a series of career video shows
are featured for visitors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
