<HEADLINE> Ramos Stresses Importance of Civil Engineering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos Thursday underscored the importance of civil engineers in
transforming the environment and helping shape the life of the
people through construction projects.
</P>
<P>
In a speech at the opening ceremony of the 1998 Civil
Engineering International Conference on Asian Infrastructure,
Sustainable Development and Project Management here, Ramos said
the civil engineer's handiwork is special in that it is meant to
last for generations and continue having an impact on economic
and social life for decades.
</P>
<P>
But he reminded civil engineers that the misuse of natural
resources, haphazard planning and irresponsible construction can
lead to catastrophic repercussions such as floods, collapse of
structures, pollution, landslides and other disasters.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting, the first international civil engineering
conference held in the Philippines, is jointly sponsored by the
American Society of Civil Engineers, Japan Society of Civil
Engineers and the Philippine Institute of Civil Engineers.
</P>
<P>
A civil engineer himself, Ramos urged his colleagues in the
profession to "keep improving our skills, to make better use of
our resources -- including our brains."
</P>
<P>
He also urged American and Japanese engineers to consider
forging strong international partnerships to meet the growing
clamor for state-of-the-art technology.  
</P>
</TEXT>
