<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Volume of Goods Transported for Foreign Trade Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 19 (Xinhua) -- China transported 400 million
tons of goods for foreign trade in 1997, an increase of 8.4
percent over 1996.
</P>
<P>
In a breakdown, exports amounted to 185 million tons and
imports to 215 million tons, according to statistics released at a
conference on transportation of foreign trade goods held recently
in Beihai city in south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
China's ports handled 10.76 million containers in
1997, and the amount of containers transported through the new
Eurasia Continental Bridge doubled that of 1996, reaching 30,016.
</P>
<P>
Freight transported by sea amounted to 350 million tons, with
exports at 160 million tons and imports at 190 million tons.
</P>
<P>
A total of 9.35 million tons of foreign trade goods were
forwarded through railways, and 640,000 tons by air.
</P>
<P>
Since China's comprehensive transportation capacity was
increaed in 1997, the contradiction between supply and
demand had been eased and the environment for transportation of
foreign trade goods relaxed, said Wei Xiaorong, director of
the Transportation Coordination Department of the Ministry of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
As the shipping capacity was over-sufficient in the
international market and charges for maritime transportation
declined greatly, the problem of ship delays in Chinese ports has
been basically solved, Wei said, adding that railway freight was
smooth in most parts of China.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the market had begun to play a major role in
adjusting the transportation and the role of administration has
been gradually weakened, he added.
</P>
<P>
Wei predicted that the deepening of the reform in China's
transportation, especially in the railway sector, will affect
the transport of foreign trade commodities this year, and
adjustment should be made to conform to the implementation of the
diversity strategy of China's foreign trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
