<HEADLINE> China Expands Secondhand-Goods Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 19 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Ministry of
Internal Trade has authorized another 20 enterprises to operate
secondhand-goods businesses, raising the total number of such
enterprises to 120.
</P>
<P>
The pilot enterprises are distributed among 92 large and
medium-sized cities in 30 provinces, autonomous regions and
municipalities. Most of them are state-owned enterprises involved
in domestic and foreign trade, finance, agriculture and post and
telecommunications, among others.
</P>
<P>
A ministry official said China's pilot program in
redistributing secondhand goods has been proceeding smoothly
during the past few years, and the circulation of secondhand goods
has become increasingly broad-based.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has urged all local departments in charge of
commercial circulation to search after rational organizing forms and
scientific management patterns for the circulation of secondhand
goods, while strengthening administration of the secondhand-goods
market to prevent illegal deals.  
</P>
