<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leprosy Patients to Enjoy Free Treatment in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Leprosy patients in Nigeria are
expected to be treated freely soon as the government is planning
to do so with the Multi-Drug Therapy (MDT) recommended by the
World Health Organization (WHO) for curing the contagious
disease.
</P>
<P>
According to Health Minister Rear Admiral Jubrila Ayinla, the
project would be supported by the Petroleum Trust Fund (PTF), set
up by the government to specialize in funding social welfare and
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The ministry and PTF were about to conclude arrangements to
facilitate the incorporation of the MDT into PTF's essential
drugs supply system, Ayinla said in the capital Abuja Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the system, PTF purchases essential drugs and provides
to all the 36 states across the country for distribution to
hospitals and health care organizations.
</P>
<P>
The measure is being adopted because most leprosy patients
could not afford the minimum cost of 80,000 Naira (about 1,000
U.S. Dollars) per patient for curing the disease, he said at a
press conference to mark the World Leprosy Day.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the number of registered leprosy
cases in the country reduced from 200,000 in 1989 to 14,000 last
year, which shows a prevalence rate of some 1.3 per 10,000
people.
</P>
<P>
This compares to the WHO eradication target of under one
leprosy case per 10,000 people as a measure of stoppage of
transmission.
</P>
<P>
Ayinla reaffirmed the country's commitment to the global
target of elimination of leprosy by the year 2000, using the MDT.
</P>
<P>
He however pointed out that the drugs available for the
treatment of leprosy for now were inadequate and were being
provided by donor agencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
