<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> (Round-up) Germany Takes Two Golds, But Austrian and DutchHave the Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Germany jumped to take two
gold medals at the 18th Olympic Winter Games on Thursday, but it was
Austrian skiier Hermann Maier and Dutch skater Marianne Timmer who
stle the limelight of the day.
</P>
<P>
German women biathletes and skiier displayed their prowess on snow
slopes, winning the women's biathlon 4x7.5km relay and the men's
slalom race respectively.
</P>
<P>
After Hilde Gerg won the slalom for Germany, the German foursome
biathletes Ursula Disl, Martina Zellner, Katrin Apel and Petra Behle
won the relay, making a revenge over their loss to Russian rivals at
the last winter Olympics in Lillehammer.
</P>
<P>
Maier, nicknamed as Herminator, won the men's giant slalom race,
the second gold medal for the iron-will skiier in the games after a
terrible crash in the downhill event.
</P>
<P>
Timmer, gold medalist in the women's 1,500 meter speed skating on
Monday, continued her bulleting speed on the ice rink Thursday
afternoon, winning the 1,000m sprint.
</P>
<P>
Germany, which lost to Russia in Lillehammer, covered the 4x7.5km
relay with a total of one hour 40 minutes and 13.6 seconds, beating
Russia to the second place by 11.6 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Norway finished third with a further 23.7 seconds behind.
</P>
<P>
Gerg outskiied world champion Deborah Compagnoni of Italy in the
women's slalom, bringing Germany their third women's Alpine crown in
Nagano following Katja Seizinger's victories in the downhill and
combined.
</P>
<P>
Gerg, who was 0.60 second behind Compagnoni after the first run,
clocked 46.51 in the second round to win the gold with an aggregate
time of one minute 32.40 seconds, a mere 0.06 second faster than the
Italian two-time Olympic champion.
</P>
<P>
Compagnoni, winner of the giant slalom at the 1994 Lillehammer
Games and the super-G event at Albertville in 1992, settled for the
silver medal after an accident-filled second run in which seven of
the first 10 skiiers tumbled out of competition.
</P>
<P>
The bronze medal went to Zali Steggall with 1:32.67, the first
Australian ever to win an Olympic medal in Alpine skiing.
</P>
<P>
Maier pulled off an Olympic golden double with victory in men's
giant slalom, which saw an early downfall of skiing legend Alberto
Tomba of Italy.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian, who suffered a bad crash in the downhill race last
Friday, proved himself the comeback king of the hill with his second
gold medal in four days.
</P>
<P>
The 25-year-old Austrian, who won the men's super-G title on Monday
on the Happo'one slope which had been his undoing in the donnhill,
prevailed in similarly swashbuckling style in the giant slalom on
Mount Higashidate.
</P>
<P>
Maier, in a class of his own in the World Cup this season, pounded
out the fastest times in both runs of the giant slalom to win by 0.85
seconds from fellow-Austrian Stefan Eberharter with a two-leg
aggregate time of two minutes 38.51 seconds on the 1,487-meter course.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland's Michael von Gruenigen prevented an Austrian medal
sweep, snatching the bronze by just 0.02 seconds from Hans Knauss,
joint silver medallist behind Maier in the super
</P>
<P>
But the race under blue sky was almost a nightmare for Tomba, who
smashed his dream to win third Olympic giant slalom gold after
crashing out early in the first run. In 1988 Calgary Games and 1992
Albertville Olympics, Tomba stormed to victories in the races.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile on the ice rink, Marianne Timmer, surprising winner in
the women's 1,500m speed skating, triumphed to take her second gold in
the games, outskating pre-race favourite world record holder Christie
Witty of the United States in M-Wave. Timmer was clocked an Olympic
record time of one minute and 16.51 seconds for the gold, the fifth
one for the Netherlands in the sport.
</P>
<P>
Witty struggled hard on the ice, but could only manage to take the
silver with 0.28 seconds behind Timmer.
</P>
<P>
"I put all out on the line, and in the last curve, I struggled a
bit," Witty said.
</P>
<P>
Canadian skater Catriona Lemay-Doan, winner in the 500m distance,
was third at 1:17.37.
</P>
<P>
Germany's strongest skater Franziska Schenk, also a medal
contender, lost her balances in the second curve and crashed against
the pad of the rink. She did not finish the race.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's competitions featured five events. The women's 500m
short track speeed skating is scheduled in the evening. Skaters from
China, South Korea, Canada and the United States are medal contenders
in the event.
</P>
<P>
Germany now leads the gold medal standings with nien golds, Russia
is second at eight and Norway third at seven. 
</P>
</TEXT>
