<HEADLINE> Japan Grants Loan to S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Japan has agreed to
grant a soft loan of 250 million Rand or 50 million U.S. Dollars
to South Africa to help modernize urban rail transport, South
African Department of Foreign Affairs said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
South African Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo and Japanese
ambassador Atushi Hatakenaka exchanged notes on the loan to South
African Rail Commuter Corporation in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Foreign Affairs said in a statement that the
25-year loan, with a seven-year grace period, carries a
concessional interest rate of 2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Japan announced an aid package of 6.24 billion Rand (1.25
billion Dollars) to South Africa in July, 1994.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's agreement was Japan's second loan to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Japan is South Africa's fourth largest trading partner, with
current two-way trade amounting to more than 16 billion Rand (3.2
billion Dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
