<HEADLINE> Ramos Urges Congress to Pass Urgent Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos Thursday made a final appeal to the congress to pass urgent
bills for enactment during the last two days of an extended
special session.
</P>
<P>
Ramos made the last-ditch effort after learning that many
members of the congress, particularly those who are running for
re-election, have shunned the special session because they are
busy campaigning.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that during the last two days of the
special session, which is the last before the May 11 elections,
senators and representatives will pass the bills he certified as
urgent.
</P>
<P>
By attending the session, he stressed, they might win more
votes than campaigning here and there.
</P>
<P>
The agenda of the special session includes the passage of the
Amnesty Proclamation Extension Bill, the Anti-Racketeering Bill,
the Police Reform Bill and the Anti-Smoking in Public Bill.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said there are many rebels who would like to avail
themselves of the amnesty but the government could do nothing at
this point if the Amnesty Proclamation Extension Bill is not
enacted during the special session.
</P>
<P>
The Anti-Racketeering Bill is also important because it will
prevent racketeering and white-collar crimes.
</P>
<P>
Another equally important bill that needs to be enacted is the
Police Reform Bill to modernize the Philippine National Police to
enable it to effectively fight crime.
</P>
<P>
The most important bill Ramos would like the congress to pass
during the special session is the long-delayed Fishery Code from
which hundreds of thousands of Filipinos will benefit.  
</P>
</TEXT>
