<HEADLINE> Philippine Ruling Party Denies Financial Squabbles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 19 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine ruling party
Thursday denied reports that the party's provincial campaign
activities have been temporarily halted due to alleged financial
squabbles.
</P>
<P>
"These reports are baseless. These are nothing but rumors
spread as part of a desperate attempt by other parties to bring
down the ruling party in the May 11 elections," said Annabelle
Abaya, the campaign spokesperson of the ruling Lakas-NUCD party.
</P>
<P>
Abaya reiterated that the campaign sorties of Lakas in the
provinces were postponed to give way to the special session of the
congress called by President Fidel Ramos to pass vital
socioeconomic reform measures.
</P>
<P>
She added that Speaker of the House of Representatives Jose de
Venecia, who is also the party's presidential candidate, has in
fact sacrificed a lot of campaigns for the national interest.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ramos said in an interview with the press that the
"so called financial squabbles" in the ruling party "are probably
being perceived."
</P>
<P>
Some local reports earlier said the ruling party's campaign
activities at the provincial level were stopped due to financial
squabbles inside the party.  
</P>
</TEXT>
