<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Trade Declines Slightly in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China's exports grew by 8.8 percent to 12.68 billion U.S.
dollars in January, while imports were 8.69 billion dollars, down
12.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Exports from state-owned enterprises were valued at 6.82
billion U.S. dollars, accounting for 53.8 percent of the total,
and those from foreign-funded enterprises were 5.45 billion
dollars, or 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
Both segments saw a decrease in imports. Foreign-invested
businesses went down 11.4 percent to 5.21 billion dollars, while
state-owned enterprises fell 14.7 percent to 3.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Processing trade accounted for 54.5 percent of the total volume,
earning 11.65 billion dollars, up 0.9 percent over the previous
year. General trade was 7.14 billion dollars, 1.3 percent down.
</P>
<P>
The equipment imported by foreign-funded businesses as
investment fell 18.4 percent to 1.47 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Influenced by the financial crisis in Southeast Asia, China's
exports to Asia declined 1.4 percent in the month to 6.99 billion
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
