<HEADLINE> Clashes Between Muslim Groups Continue in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Sporadic clashes between
members of two Muslim groups continued in the southern province of
Cotabato, the Philippine News Agency reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a military spokesman as saying the crossfire
between members of the Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) and
Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) started Monday night and was
still going on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
There were no reported casualties from both sides and no report
of mass evacuation by residents, said Rosque Garingalao, spokesman
of the army's Sixth Infantry Division.
</P>
<P>
Garingalao said MILF rebels stormed the villages of Naangan and
Simuni, both run by the MNLF under Commander Dimalao Ambel, thus
leading to the encounter.
</P>
<P>
He said the military are still looking into the probable motive
behind the attack but hinted, "This might be the result of a
continuous grudge between the two forces that still needs patching
up."
</P>
<P>
Garingalao said the military have already mobilized the 602nd
Brigade in the area to act as peacekeepers before the situation
gets worse.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, MILF guerrillas also attacked Dug-ong, another
MNLF-run village and left four MILF rebels killed and six others
wounded when members of the two groups were engaged in an ensuing
clash.
</P>
<P>
The military said the MILF was imposing forced taxation in
Dug-ong which the MNLF did not like, resulting in a showdown.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, a breakaway faction from the MNLF and now the biggest
Muslim rebel group in the country, has refused to be part of a
peace accord signed between the MNLF and the government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
