<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 08:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Steps up Efforts to End Iraq Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 19 (Xinhua) -- On the eve of a visit to
Baghdad by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, Iran has stepped up
its efforts to bring a peaceful end to the Iraq crisis by
coordinating with regional countries.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi Wednesday exchanged
views on the Iraq crisis with his Syrian, Omani and Yemeni
counterparts through telephone calls and held two rounds of talks
with his visiting Iraqi counterpart Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf, the
Iranian official news agency IRNA reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi and the foreign ministers from the four regional
countries discussed the possible diplomatic solution to the
standoff between Iraq and the U.N. over arms inspection.
</P>
<P>
All the five foreign ministers stressed the need for stepping
up diplomatic endeavors to defuse a U.S. military attack on Iraq
by supporting Annan's visit to Baghdad, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahhaf once again called on Iran, chairman of the
Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC), to continue its
efforts to avert a U.S. strike on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian foreign minister said that Iran would do all within
its power to prevent such a military action.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the implementation of the U.N. Security
Council resolutions needs no force, rather it is possible through
the cooperation between Iraq and the U.N. arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq al-Sharaa and Kharrazi expressed
optimism that a close and coordinated cooperation between Iraq
and the U.N. chief in the implementation of the U.N. Security
Council resolutions would be helpful in defusing the crisis.
</P>
<P>
They also said that a U.S. military strike on Iraq was
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Yemeni Foreign Minister Abdul-Karim al-Iryani
announced that Yemen was fully prepared to closely cooperate and
coordinate with Iran in trying to find a peaceful solution to the
Iraq-U.N. standoff triggered off by Iraq's refusal to allow
U.N. inspectors unfettered access to all sites suspected of hiding
banned weapons.
</P>
<P>
As the United States and Britain are strengthening their
military buildup in the Persian Gulf to prepare a military strike
on Iraq, regional countries pinned their hope on the forthcoming
visit of the U.N. chief to Baghdad to avoid a military
confrontation in the region.
</P>
<P>
Annan has announced that he would go to Iraq on Friday to
continue his efforts to solve the crisis peacefully.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi foreign minister arrived here Wednesday morning in a
bid to seek more support from Tehran. This was his second visit to
Iran within a month. His last visit came in January.
</P>
<P>
Worrying about the impacts of the possible U.S. military
attack on Iraq, particularly the possible shift of power in
Baghdad and Iraq's disintegration, Tehran has strongly expressed
its opposition to any military attack, calling for diplomatic
efforts to end the Iraq crisis peacefully. 
</P>
</TEXT>
