<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Lists Top Ten Archeological Finds for 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Archeologists also unearthed a smaller, but older ancient city
in Henan Province. They estimate the city was built when the Shang
Dynasty (1600-1100 B.C.) defeated the Xia Dynasty (2100-1600 B.C.).
</P>
<P>
The extensive archeological site provides important clues to
accurately determine the periods of China's three earlist
dynasties -- Xia, Shang and Zhou.
</P>
<P>
A number of expers rated the most valuable find of the year as
the 334 ritual and musical instruments unearthed at a sacrificial
site in Henan Province.
</P>
<P>
The find included a bronze Ding (three-legged tripod, or
four-legged cauldron) and Zhong (bell) crafted during the Spring
and Autumn Period (770-476 B.C.). The well-preserved large pieces
feature beautiful decorations.
</P>
<P>
The Qin Dynasty (221-207 B.C) imperial summer resort and
bathhouse unearthened in Liaoning Province will prove highly
valuable for further studies of Qin architecture, art, religion
and technology. The site was excavated over a period of five years.
</P>
<P>
Perhaps the most conspicuous find in terms of ancient
architecture centers on a large channel built with stone which was
discovered in the palace ruins of the southern king during the
Western Han Dynasty (206 BC-24 A.D.). The ruins were discovered in
central part of Guangzhou, Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
The stone channel extends to a stone pond in the shape of a
crescent moon, with the configuration representing one of the
major scenic sites in the magnificent royal garden.
</P>
<P>
Archeologically speaking, the "youngest" find on list was
represented by the excavation of 110 tombs dating to the Kingdom
of Loulan (Kroraina) which thrived along the ancient Silk
Road. The tombs, which date back at least 1,500 years, yielded
over 200 artifacts, including articles made of wool, silk, wood,
and glass, as well as pottery and lacquerware.
</P>
<P>
Selection of the annual top ten archaeological finds was
initiated in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
