<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Lists Top Ten Archeological Finds for 1997 (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 19 (Xinhua) -- China has selected its Top Ten
archeological finds for 1997, including the world's oldest known
rice paddy, 2,000-year-old stone structures rivaling those found
in Greece and Rome, an imperial summer resort and bathhouse dating
back over 2,000 years, and more than 100 tombs along the ancient
Silk Road.
</P>
<P>
The Top Ten list was selected from 479 archeological projects
carried out during 1997. Leading Chinese archeologists noted that
the finds were quite satisfying, despite the lack of highly
significant discoveries.
</P>
<P>
The oldest find, which dates back over 300,000 years, included
more than 30,000 stoneware items found in a cave in Luonan County,
Shanxi Province. "The stoneworks date to the Early Stone Age in a
place south of the Qinling Ranges," according to experts.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists working in Zhangqiu, Shandong Province, unearthed
19 cave dwellings with above rooms. The archeologists described
the find as the "best preserved dwellings from the Neolithic
Age". The dwellings, which date back at least 7,700 years,
contained cauldrons, jars, kettles and stoneware.
</P>
<P>
A mound site with a history of between 5,000-6,000 years was
discovered in south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region
during the summer of 1997. Archeologists also excavated 149 tombs
in the region and for the first time found evidence of
dismemberment during burial.
</P>
<P>
Experts working in central China's Hunan Province found traces
of the world's oldest rice paddy dating back over 6,500 years.
</P>
<P>
One of the most significant archeological finds in 1997 was
unearthered in the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region. Excavation of housing complex and 20 tombs dating between
the Neolithic Age and Early Bronze Age yielded a large array of
pottery, stoneware and jade items.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
