<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Health Minister Urges to Fight Smoking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 19 (Xinhua) -- South African Health
Minister Nkosazana Zuma has urged the people of the whole country
to fight smoking habit.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a conference of international tobacco control
experts at Sea Point, Cape Town Wednesday, Zuman said it was time
to change society's relatively benign tolerance of tobacco.
</P>
<P>
The mistaken impressions about the importance of tobacco to
the economy should be corrected, Zuma said.
</P>
<P>
The three-day conference, entitled Economics of Tobacco
Control, is being hosted by the University of Cape Town and the
Medical Research Council and has drawn delegates from 17
countries.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was designed to share research findings with
scientists worldwide, invites debate with researchers from the
tobacco industry and intends to formulate policy proposals for
tobacco control.
</P>
<P>
Zuma quoted researchers as saying that there were about three
million deaths worldwide each year from tobacco-related
illnesses, and an estimated 30 million people would be killed
this decade by smoking.
</P>
<P>
She said while fewer people were smoking in industrialized
countries, there were an estimated 800 million people who smoked
in the developing world and the number was increasing.
</P>
<P>
"Lung cancer is the most common cancer in the world and 85
percent of cases in men and 46 percent in women are due to
tobacco."
</P>
<P>
It was reported that tobacco use in South Africa was
declining, with consumption falling at a rate of three percent a
year since 1990.
</P>
<P>
Zuma said surveys showed the number of smokers had dropped
from 30.2 percent of the population in 1996 to 28.4 percent in
1997.
</P>
<P>
For years, the tobacco industry repeatedly emphasized the
importance of tobacco to the economy, the number of jobs it
created and the tax revenue it generated.
</P>
<P>
Yet a 1993 World Bank study estimated that tobacco use
resulted in a global net loss of 200 billion U.S. Dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
"This is more than the total current health expenditures in
all developed countries combined," Zuma said.
</P>
<P>
It was currently believed that the best weapon the South
African government had to deter smoking was taxation, the price
at which cigarettes were sold.
</P>
<P>
Zuma said the government was considering to amend the current
legislation so as to ban smoking in public and in the work place.
</P>
<P>
"We may ban tobacco advertizing, sponsorships and promotions,
and raise to 18 the age at which minors can buy cigarettes," she
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets Japanese Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
stressed today that the development of Sino-Japanese relations
should be based on the Sino-Japanese Joint Statement and the
Sino-Japanese Treaty of Peace and Friendship.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made the remark here this morning in a meeting with Isamu
Takada, governor of the Nagasaki Prefecture of Japan, and his
party.
</P>
<P>
Extending a welcome to Takada, an old friend of the Chinese
people, Jiang pointed to the helpful work done by Takada and the
Nagasaki Prefecture in past decades for the promotion of
Sino-Japanese friendly relations.
</P>
<P>
Stating that this is the 20th anniversary of the bilateral
treaty of peace and friendship, Jiang said that the development of
bilateral relations has generally been good since the
normalization of bilateral diplomatic ties.
</P>
<P>
Sino-Japanese relations will face the 21st century and enter an
important period which is a juncture linking the past and the
future, added Jiang.
</P>
<P>
On historical issues, Jiang said that Japanese aggression
against China initiated by the Japanese militarists caused great
suffering to the people of both China and Japan, including people
of the Nagasaki Prefecture.
</P>
<P>
Quoting a Chinese saying that "past experience, if not
forgotten, can be a guide for the future," Jiang pointed out that
Sino-Japanese friendship from generation to generation can be
realized so long as Japan's younger generation is educated with
correct historical knowledge.
</P>
<P>
Jiang expressed his appreciation for the efforts made by
Japanese figures of insight for the promotion of bilateral
friendship.
</P>
<P>
Takada said that Nagasaki Prefecture, which took the lead among
Japanese autonomous bodies in passing a resolution demanding
normalization of Japan-China relations, has followed the spirit of
the bilateral treaty of peace and friendship in past decades and
conducted wide-ranging friendly exchanges in various fields with
China.
</P>
<P>
He said he will, as always, continue to play an active role in
Japanese autonomous bodies in promoting the development of
Japan-China friendship.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese visitors are here as guests of the China
Association for International Friendly Contacts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
