<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Slightly Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Australian shares closed
slightly weaker Thursday as uncertainty about the economic outlook
discouraged local investors from following Wall Street's lead.
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries closed down 2.4 points, or 0.09 percent, at
2658.8. Overnight, the Dow climbed 52.56 points, or 0.63 percent,
to 8451.06.
</P>
<P>
Macquarie Equities broker Lucinda Chan said trade was volatile,
with commodity-based stocks and banks undermining the overall
performance.
</P>
<P>
"I think the market generally lacks confidence at the moment,"
Chan said.
</P>
<P>
The All Industrials gained 4.9 points, or 0.11 percent, to
4556.7 while the All Resources lost 9.5 points, or 0.82 percent,
to reach 1145.
</P>
<P>
The bank index closed marginally higher, up 2.8 points to
5357.1 with shares in Commonwealth Bank dragging back the index by
closing 9 cents lower at 17.75 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Westpac bank finished up half a cent to 9.99 Australian dollars
while ANZ shares closed flat at 9.54 Australian dollars and
National Australia Bank shares at 19.8 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Major diversified miner BHP lost 8 cents to close at 14.42
Australian dollars and Rio Tinto fell 21.3 cents to 18.987
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index dropped 6.3 points, or 0.56 percent, to 1120.9,
despite a slight rise in the spot value of gold bullion.
</P>
<P>
Gold bullion closed at 298.25 U.S. dollars in Sydney, up 1 U.S.
dollar from Wednesday night's close.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was registered at 319.99 million valued at
592.1 million U.S. dollars with falls outnumbering rises 561 to
517.  
</P>
