<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Visitors Enjoy Deng Photo Exhibition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 19 (Xinhua) -- A retired Beijing teacher
arrived at the China Military Museum early this morning to visit a
photo exhibition presented by Deng Lin, daughter of late Chinese
leader Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
The visitor carried a book on Deng's life and carefully
surveyed the 112 photographs on exhibit with tears in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
"I feel that Deng is still amongst the people," said the
teacher.
</P>
<P>
Deng, the architect of China's reform and opening, passed away
on February 19 last year at the age of 93. Deng Lin, the late
leader's eldest daughter, joined in commemorative activities to
mark the first anniversary of her father's death by presenting the
first public exhibition of photographs showing his daily life
activities.
</P>
<P>
"My father enjoyed hobbies and just like everybody who
experienced joy, anger and sorrow. Deng Xiaoping not only served
as the nation's leader, but was also a good son, good husband and
good father," said Deng Lin.
</P>
<P>
She noted that her father was unaware when most of the
photographs were being snapped.
</P>
<P>
Many visitors learned for the first time that Deng liked to
read works about legendary figures, enjoyed playing with his
grandchildren, and liked to take walks in the snow.
</P>
<P>
One photo showed Deng and his grandsons planting a tree in
suburban Beijing. Deng, in fact, advocated the "Green China" drive
some 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The total number of trees China has planted since that time
would cover an area the size of Switzerland. Beijing citizens, who
formerly suffered from strong winds and blowing sand, have greatly
benefitted from the afforestation effort.
</P>
<P>
The photographs were taken between 1980-1993, a period which
Deng Lin cites highly important for both her father and the
Chinese nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos Predicts Rebound for Asian Economies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos Thursday predicted that Asia will soon rebound from the
current economic turmoil and the Philippines "will be right on top
of that rebound."
</P>
<P>
"Mark my word," Ramos told more than 600 participants in the
1998 Civil Engineering International Conference on Asian
Infrastructure, Sustainable Development and Project Management
here.
</P>
<P>
"In spite of the turmoil, Asia will rebound. It is just a
question of when and how soon," Ramos said at the opening ceremony
of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The economic setback, he said, "may even strengthen our
institutions in the long run. What is important is that we are not
only surviving, but we are adjusting, we are adopting and we are
formulating creative responses to the crisis."
</P>
<P>
The currency meltdown started last July with Thailand being the
first country in Southeast Asia to be hit by the crisis when its
baht dived considerably.
</P>
<P>
The contagion affected Indonesia and Malaysia when their
currencies also depreciated to a record low.
</P>
<P>
For a while, the Philippines warded off the currency attack but
the peso later stumbled. From an exchange rate of 26 pesos to a
U.S. dollar, the peso declined to 30 and 35 and even reached as
low as 46 to the greenback.
</P>
<P>
But Ramos said the economic fundamentals adopted by his
administration have prevented the peso from further devaluation.
</P>
<P>
In recent weeks, the peso has appreciated from 46 to 39.1 to
the dollar.
</P>
<P>
According to Ramos, Asia may have fallen victim to its rapid
success in the past decade. However, he remained optimistic that
the Philippines and other Asian countries affected by the economic
turmoil will recover soon.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Import 1.2 Million Tons of Cereals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 19 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Food and Agriculture
Organization (FAO) has predicted that kenya would need to import
1.2 million tons of cereals including wheat and rice as a result
of the extensive crop destruction caused by the El Nino rains.
</P>
<P>
In a special report on the African food situation, FAO said
that the heavy rains, particularly in November and January,
adversely affected the 1997/98 maize crop, the staple crop for
Kenyans.
</P>
<P>
The torrential rains in October/November at the time of the
harvest of the main season crop reduced the yields of maize
already affected by a dry spell at the critical grain filling
stage.
</P>
<P>
The worst effect of the floods was on second-season crops
grown in the bi-modal rainfall areas of Western, Central and
Eastern provinces from mid-October to February.
</P>
<P>
The maize output of this season is estimated to have declined
by one-third from the normal levels while the bean crop was
sharply reduced due to both adverse weather and lack of seed.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the 1997/98 (September/August) maize
production is estimated at 2.3 million tons, slightly above the
1996/97 level but below the average of the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Maize import requirements, expected to be covered mainly
commercially, are estimated at 800,000 tons which is lower than
in the previous year when maize imports reached one million tons,
the report added.
</P>
<P>
The areas worst-affected by the El Nino-induced heavy rains
include Coast and Northeastern provinces, and parts of Eastern
Province which have been declared disaster zones by the kenyan
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
