<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Trade Surplus Up in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Japan, by exporting more and
importing less, ran a merchandise trade surplus of 381.5 billion
yen (about 3.02 billion U.S. dollars) in January.
</P>
<P>
The year's first month, the Finance Ministry said Thursday, was
the 10th month in a row to witness the country's favorable balance
on rise, and the 30th month to see its exports increasing.
</P>
<P>
The monthly surplus, partly the result of 3,853.7 billion yen
(30.58 billion dollars) in exports, was a sharp contrast to the
deficit of 24.5 billion yen (194 million dollars) a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Together with the 8.8 percent year-to-year hike of exports was
a 2.6 percent reduction, to 3,472.2 billion yen (27.5 billion
dollars) in January, of Japan's imports, said the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Japan's politically sensitive trade surplus with the United
States jumped 65.7 percent from a year before to 493.9 billion yen
(3.91 billion dollars), rising for the 16th straight month.
</P>
<P>
Of the total U.S. trade volume, Japan's exports advanced 20.7
percent to 1,274.4 billion yen (10 billion dollars) while imports
was up 3.0 percent to 780.5 billion yen (6.19 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, its trade with financially troubled Asian nations
dropped in January, resulting in a deficit of 34.3 billion yen
(270 million dollars) for the first time since January 1990.
</P>
<P>
The surplus with the European Union more than doubled from a
year earlier, totaling 186.4 billion yen (1.46 billion dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
