<HEADLINE> E. African Road Program to Be Discussed in Arusha </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 19 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank and European
Union are willing to co-sponsor a donors meeting to discuss an
East African Road Network Program in May in Arusha, northern
Tanzania, according to a Kenya Times report Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Nicholas Biwott, Minister for East African
and Regional Cooperation, as saying Wednesday that Belgium, Japan
and the United States would participate in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The program is aimed at improving the road network in Kenya,
Tanzania and Uganda in a bid to facilitate the evolving East
African Cooperation Common Market at a cost of 4.2 billion U.S.
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Biwott made the remarks after he came back from a visit to
Brussels, Tokyo, Washington and London with Tanzanian Foreign
Minister Jakaya Kikwete and Ugandan Minister Rebecca Kadaga.
</P>
<P>
He noted that The ministerial delegation's visit was designed
to brief the various capitals on the objectives, priorities and
activities of the East African Cooperation (EAC).
</P>
<P>
The private sectors in the four capitals had widely
participated in discussions with the delegation led by the
Tanzanian minister who is the current Chairman of the Tripartite
Commission for EAC, the Kenyan minister said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Tanzanian Foreign Minister Kikwete told a
press conference in London Monday that the critical issue for the
future success of the EAC was the development of the region's
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that there were five priority sectors, that is,
telecommunications, railways, civil aviation, roads and energy.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement issued after the visit, the three
ministers said that the common market was becoming a major
investment center with countries such as the United States and
United Kingdom having already embarked on programs to mobilize
their private sectors to expand their business investments in the
East African region.
</P>
<P>
It is the first ministerial delegation abroad from the EAC
since the regional arrangement was re-launched in November, 1993
and the establishment of the Secretariat in March, 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
