<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Philippines Acts to Lower Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Eight months after the currency
crisis started in Southeast Asia, sweeping countries including the
Philippines, the monetary authorities here have shifted their
focus from defending the peso to reducing the interest rates which
are killing the economy.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Central Bank jacked up its overnight borrowing
and lending rates to ward off speculators when the currency crisis
began last July. To protect their own benefits, commercial banks
also hiked their interest rates. The inter-bank overnight
borrowing rate even jumped to a record high of 160 percent at one
time.
</P>
<P>
The measures, however, have not stabilized the Philippine
currency as expected. In fact, the high interest rates themselves
have become a crisis and begun to put a great strain on the
country's economy.
</P>
<P>
During the past few months, the prime lending rates have
averaged out at 30 percent in the Philippines, leaving companies
either too scared to borrow or compounded by tighter credit. As a
result, some enterprises have been forced to reduce production or
simply shut down while some others had to apply for moratoria on
loans payments.
</P>
<P>
In the long run, the high interest rates are more harmful than
a volatile peso because they would deal a heavy blow to the
manufacturing sector, the pillar of the country's economic growth.
Pinched by both the high interest rates and the declining peso,
manufacturers in the southern Philippines have decided to boycott
loans payments.
</P>
<P>
The central bank has repeatedly called on commercial banks to
lower their interest rates and it took the lead by cutting its
overnight lending rate to 15 percent and the banks' liquidity
reserve rate to 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the central bank's move has allowed the
banks to have 48 billion pesos (1.2 billion U.S. dollars) more in
liquidity and should therefore help bring down the interest rates.
</P>
<P>
However, the banks failed to follow suit, making a
congressional committee believe that there is a cartel in the
banking industry which is profiteering from the high rates.
</P>
<P>
Tired of resorting to moral suasion, central bank governor
Gabriel Singson threatened to regulate the prime lending rates,
saying the rates must go down to just three percentage points
above the 91-day Treasury bill rate which currently stands at
around 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
The business community voiced its support for Singson's plan.
Raul Concepcion, president of the Federation of Philippine
Industries, said this would be the best way to force banks to cut
lending rates.
</P>
<P>
President Fidel Ramos also called for new strategies to slash
the interest rates at a recent national economic meeting attended
by 350 representatives from all walks of life.
</P>
<P>
"We uphold the importance of downing inflation. We underscore
the importance of minimizing exchange rate fluctuations. But even
as we do so, let us not kill the economic recovery with high
interest rates," he said.
</P>
<P>
Under pressure from both the government and the private sector,
the 53 commercials banks in the country came to a gentleman's
agreement with the Bankers Association of the Philippines, under
which the prime lending rate will be cut by one percentage point
per week until it reaches about 21 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, two leading insurance systems, the Government
Service Insurance System and the Social Security System, have also
made efforts to help cut down the interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Each of them has agreed to set up a 5 billion peso facility
(about 125 million dollars) to lend at lower than market rates to
small- and medium-sized enterprises and export-oriented firms,
which are the hardest-hit in the currency crisis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Conduct Crime Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 19 (Xinhua) -- A "scientific" survey
will be conducted in South Africa next month to determine the
levels of crime and public perceptions, The Citizen daily said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-funded survey will poll 5,000 households throughout
South Africa, Bernie Fanaroff, head of the National Crime
Prevention Strategy, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The survey could be used as a base line against which levels
of crime could be judged objectively in future, with similar
surveys made each few years, he said.
</P>
<P>
There was a controversy over the actual crime level in the
country. The government repeatedly quoted official statistics as
showing that all serious crimes except rape were declining, but
opposition parties questioned the validity of the surveys.
</P>
<P>
Fanaroff defended the validity of of statistics and said the
public confidence in government's anti-crime strategy would grow.
</P>
<P>
But he admitted that the criminal justice system had not been
operating in such a way as to deter crime, because criminals did
not feel certain that they would be detected, arrested, charged,
tried and "put away".
</P>
<P>
"There is no doubt that our levels of serious crime are too
high, particularly in Johannesburg," he said.
</P>
<P>
There is no death penalty in South Africa and suspects, even
involved in serious crimes, could obtain bail easily. There were
also allegations that criminals won police cooperation in prison
escapes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
