<HEADLINE> Beijing Developing New Tourist Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 19 (Xinhua) -- With the monetary crisis in
Southeast Asia starting to affect China's tourist market, travel
agencies in the Chinese capital plan to develop new tourist
sources in Russia and India.
</P>
<P>
The tourism business will keep its markets open in Europe, the
Americas, and Japan.
</P>
<P>
In January, there was 2.6 percent growth in the number of
foreign tourists in Beijing from the year-ago period, but the
number of tourists from Thailand and Republic of Korea dropped 50
percent, and from Malaysia, 26.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The devaluation of their currencies has at the same time made
Southeast Asian countries strong rivals for the Chinese tourism
business. Beijing gets about 60 percent of its foreign visitors
from Asia, with Southeast Asian countries accounting for a third
of that. Forty percent come from Europe, the Americas, and
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
Beijing had 2.28 million overseas tourists last year, bringing
in 2.25 billion US dollars worth of foreign exchange. This year,
the city expects a five percent growth in both figures.  
</P>
</TEXT>
