<HEADLINE> Textile Industry in Central China Province Becomes Profitable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Henan Province in central
China has succeeded in transforming its financially-troubled
textile sector into a profitable one.
</P>
<P>
Textile mills in Henan turned a profit of 46 million yuan in
1997 after three consecutive years of economic losses.
</P>
<P>
A provincial official attributed the turnaround to a
spindle-reduction campaign, mergers, readjusting the product mix
and improving management.
</P>
<P>
The No. 1 Silk and Flax Printing and Dying Mill, the biggest
money-losing enterprise in the textile industry of Henan, merged
with the Shenma Group last year.
</P>
<P>
Nanyang Cotton Mill purchased a bankrupt operation at 80
million yuan and took over the 50,000 spindles lying idle.
</P>
<P>
Losses incurred by cotton mills in Zhengzhou, the provincial
capital, were reduced by 50 million yuan last year.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to make greater successes, the provincial government
has decided to eliminate 765,000 outmoded spindles in the coming
three years to dovetail with the national spindle-cut drive. The
scheme is expected to affect 29,000 textile workers in
Henan.
</P>
<P>
About 261,000 spindles will be abandoned and 4,500 workers laid
off this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
