<HEADLINE> Chengdu Witnessed High Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Chengdu, capital of Sichuan
Province in southwest China, generated 101 billion yuan (12.2
billion US dollars) in gross domestic products in 1997.
</P>
<P>
This made Chengdu the second largest GDP producer in western
China, only after Chongqing Municipality.
</P>
<P>
Chengdu recorded economic growth of over 11.5 percent in 1996
and 1997 and the city ranked 12th among Chinese cities in overall
economic strength.
</P>
<P>
Scientific and technical progress is now accountable to 43
percent of the city's economic growth, as compared with 30 percent
in 1987, city officials said.
</P>
<P>
The officials attributed the economic growth to the commercial
sector, which accounted for one third of the city's revenue and
whose proportion in GDP was the second highest in the country.
</P>
<P>
The efficiency of the local industry has also been remarkably
improved as 90 percent of the city's state-owned small enterprises
have undergone transformation by means of merger, bankruptcy and
laying off workers. Meanwhile, large conglomerates have been
formed.
</P>
<P>
The city's grain output hit a record 4.02 million tons
last year. 
</P>
