<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Systematic Doping in Chinese Swimming, FINA Says (2-last) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Following are the measures and penalties that the CSA has
decided to take in order to eliminate drug-taking in swimming:
</P>
<P>
1. To strengthen its education program related to anti-doping,
the Chinese Swimming Association will hold a working meeting
annually regarding anti-doping issues.
</P>
<P>
The main purpose of the meeting will be to have anti-doping
known to everybody and let all people in China's swimming circle
gain a thorough knowledge of the bad effect and harm of doping and
to fight against all kinds of banned substances conscientiously.
</P>
<P>
2. The CSA shall perfect its regulations on anti-doping without
diminishing the legal rights of swimmers and coaches.
</P>
<P>
3. The registration system shall be improved so that any
swimmers who has registered to participate in national
competitions must first sign a letter of guarantee not to use any
banned substances.
</P>
<P>
4. All local clubs and local swimming associations shall be
required to execute a letter of guarantee to enhance the
management of the swimmers in order to eliminate any doping cases.
</P>
<P>
5. The CSA shall intensify its test methods, increase the
tesing number (to 600 in 1998) and impose more severe sanctions.
</P>
<P>
When a swimmer is found using banned substances listed in FINA
Rule 9.2(a) for the first time, he/she shall be banned for life;
for other banned substances, the penalty shall also be more strict
than FINA Rules.
</P>
<P>
6. Because coaches have such a great responsibility for the
actions of their swimmers, coaches whose swimmers test positive
shall also by severely punished without the necessity of proof of
action or knowledge that the swimmer has taken banned substances.
</P>
<P>
7. If a club or a local association has been found with two
positive cases within 12 months, it shall be suspended from
domestic and international competition for 12 months and fined.
</P>
<P>
If four positive tests are found within four years, the club or
association shall be suspended from any domestic and international
competition, and disqualified from participation in the next
National Games or National City Games.
</P>
<P>
8. To strictly limit the amount of money awarded to swimmers
and coaches. Local clubs or local associations are not allowed to
give cash rewards directly to swimmers or coaches.
</P>
<P>
All cash rewards shall be put into the Bank by the Chinese
Swimming Association until the retirement of such swimmer, at that
time, cash rewards as well as the bank interest will be given to
him or her, and coaches may have the rewards after four years if
none of their swimmers test positive for any banned substances;
otherwise, all the honors shall be deprived and money shall be
confiscated.
</P>
<P>
9. The Chinese Swimming Association shall announce immediately
to the public any sanction to swimmers and coaches in order to
enhance the supervisory from all societies.
</P>
<P>
10. The Chinese Swimming Association shall suggest to state
authorities concerned to strengthen the criminal penalties for
doping, so that the use of doping in sports can be brought up as a
legal responsibility.
</P>
<P>
11. The Chinese Swimming Association shall make further
cooperation with FINA and FINA's member federations by inviting
coaches and other technical personnel to visit Chinese swimming
programs at their own expense, and by making other joint efforts
to fight against doping.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Police Says Recent Bomb Threats Untrue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian police has said no
real bombs were found in the bomb threats received by many
quarters in the country recently.
</P>
<P>
The bomb threats against a few office buildings in Jakarta and
Medan, North Sumatra province, as well as against an air-borne
aircraft all proved to be untrue, official Antara News Agency
Thursday quoted Spokesman of the Indonesian State Police Brig Gen.
Dai Bachtiar as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said security officers never found any package in which a
real bomb of low or high technology is usually contained.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the public should remain alert and not panic
when threatened.
</P>
<P>
Bachtiar said whether bomb threats were real or not real,
police and other security authorities were at all times ready to
secure up to 10 bomb threats in different places at the same time.
</P>
<P>
A bomb threat Wednesday led to the evacuation of hundreds of
workers from a shopping center building in West Jakarta's business
district.
</P>
<P>
After receiving a phone call, saying a time-bomb was planted at
the Gajah Mada Plaza Shopping center about mid-day, police sealed
off the building and hundreds of shop and office workers were
evacuated immediately and the traffic was also stopped. But the
police officers found nothing suspicious.
</P>
<P>
The threat was the latest in a series of hoaxes in recent days
being sent to office buildings in the capital city.
</P>
<P>
At least 12 bomb hoaxes have been reported at office buildings
and public facilities since the January 18 bomb blast at a Tanah
Tinggi apartment in Central Jakarta during which two people were
injured.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the general session of the People's Consultative
Assembly (MPR) scheduled for next month, Bachtiar said people
should help make the five-yearly event a success.
</P>
<P>
The MPR will meet from March 1 to 11 to elect the country's next
president and vice president as well as establish the state policy
guideline for the 1998-2003 period.
</P>
<P>
About the riots triggered by price hike that recently took place
in several places in Java as well as outside Java, the spokesman
said that based on information from those seized during the
incidents, security authorities believe the actions were
masterminded by certain quarters.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the security authorities had not yet come to
any conclusions about them so far.
</P>
<P>
According to Jakarta police, hundreds people, who protested
against the soaring prices of staple commodities amid the
debilitating economic crisis, have been arrested in the last few
weeks in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
