<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Crisis Critical in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Food shortages in the West
African state of Sierra Leone will remain critical, even though
peace-keeping forces have regained control the capital of
Freetown, the U.N. Food and Agriculture Oganization (FAO) said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The FAO said that with the recapture of Freetown from a
military junta, the economic embargo imposed since last August may
be eased or lifted, allowing an increase in food imports.
</P>
<P>
However, as much as 80,000 tonnes of food aid may be required
this year, the FAO said.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone's cereal import requirement for 1998 totals about
260,000 tonnes, but lifting of the embargo would enable local
traders to import only 180,000 tonnes.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone army officers led by Major Johnny Paul Korma ended
a short experiment in democracy with a coup on May 25,
1997. Forces sent in by the Economic Community of West African
States recaptured Freetown from the rebels last weekend.
</P>
<P>
But an FAO official said fighting may spread to rural areas which
have been relatively calm since the coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
