<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Hopes to Set up Asia-Europe Trade, Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 19 (Xinhua) -- The Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) hopes that an Asia-Europe Trade
and Investment Fund to be set up at the Asia-Europe Meeting (ASEM)
in London in April to renew faith among the European communities
in the region's economy, visiting Thai Foreign Minister Surin
Pitsuwan said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We want something concrete, something that would bring
confidence in the regional economy," he said at a news conference
after meeting Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim here.
</P>
<P>
The fund could revive the economy and bring back confidence in
the region, he said, adding "We need participation from
outside...with the Europeans who have faith in us as they have
shown two years ago in Bangkok, with enthusiasm and commitment."
</P>
<P>
The problem faced in the region is the lack of funding and lack
of liquidity, therefore it would be good if liquidity could be
accessed in the region, Surin said.
</P>
<P>
He said: "At least I can speak on behalf of ASEAN that we would
like to see something concrete not only just warm words,
comforting words, but something like a fund to promote trade in
the region."
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. Seven members would
attend the coming London meeting, which is the second in the
series as Laos and Myanmar are being excluded.
</P>
<P>
ASEM held its inaugural meeting in Bangkok in 1996 which was
also attended by the 15-member European Union (UE) and three of
Asian economic powers -- China, South Korea and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Surin arrived here Wednesday afternoon for a two-day visit to
Malaysia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
