<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Systematic Doping in Chinese Swimming, FINA Says (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 19 (Xinhua) -- An International Swimming
Federation (FINA) delegation said here on Thursday that they
believed there was no systematic doping in the Chinese swimming.
</P>
<P>
"The inquires of the FINA delegation has led to the belief that
the Chinese Swimming Association (CSA) is not a participant of any
systematic process of doping in swimming," the delegation said in
a statement issued on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The five-member delegation arrived here on Monday to investigate
the CSA's probe into two doping cases which involved five Chinese
swimmers.
</P>
<P>
Four swimmers tested positive for the banned drug Triamterene
(diuretic) in January's World Swimming Championships in Perth,
Australia, following the discovery of human growth hormones in the
baggage of Chinese swimmer Yuan Yuan.
</P>
<P>
The FINA delegation said that the discovery of Triamterene in
the urine sample of Wang Wei, Zhang Yi, Wang Luna and Cai Huijue
has been confirmed by the testing of the B sample by the
IOC-sanctioned Sydney laboratory.
</P>
<P>
The final sanctions on the four swimmers will be announced
after the hearing of the FINA doping panel in Lausanne on March
14, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The FINA delegation was headed by FINA co-vice president Ross
Wales of the United States. The other members are FINA co-vice
president Roger Smith of Australia, FINA Bureau members Sam
Ramsamy of South Africa and Pipat Paniangvait of Thailand, and
FINA senior official Cornel Marculescu of Sweden.
</P>
<P>
After their arrival, the delegation met with the Chinese
leading sports officials, medical and anti-doping experts and the
four swimmers who tested positive in Perth and their coaches.
</P>
<P>
The delegation concluded that the CSA failed to do a good job
in control of swimmers and coaches.
</P>
<P>
"The delegation was disappointed to deduce that the Chinese
Swimming Association did not exercise total control in the whole
country. It exercises little control over provincial swimming and
over coaches," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Nevertheless, it was pleasing to note that the Chinese
Swimming Association has recognized this problem and has agree, in
conjunction with the Chinese Olympic Committee, to adopt a series
of measures and penalties to overcome this issue," FINA Bureau
member Ramsamy said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Deputy PM on Annan's Iraq Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
was warned against refusing the United Nations' attempt at
mediation in the weapons inspection crisis by Italian Deputy Prime
Minister Walter Veltroni on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's diplomatic mission to
Baghdad on Friday will mark the re-emergence of the U.N. as the
main protagonist in the weapons inspection crisis, said Veltroni.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General, in deciding to go to Baghdad, had taken
over responsibility for the international response to the Iraq
crisis - which until now had been led by the United States, said
Veltroni.
</P>
<P>
If Saddam Hussein refused Annan's attempts at mediation, "he
should be aware that he would be saying no directly to the U.N.,"
Veltroni warned.
</P>
<P>
"This would change the scenario on which our discussions till
now have been based," he said. "It would amount to a challenge to
the U.N., not to a single country, and would demand that everyone
react accordingly."
</P>
<P>
Rome clearly preferred a peaceful solution to the crisis, but
Prime Minister Romano Prodi has said that if it came to the
crunch, Italy would not desert its allies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
