<HEADLINE> Chinese Defense Minister Completes Australia Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Defense Minister Chi
Haotian left Sydney at noon on Thursday for China following his
six-day visit to Australia.
</P>
<P>
Among those who saw the Chinese minister and his party off were
Rear Admiral Chiris Ritchie and Chinese Ambassador to Australia
Hua Junduo.
</P>
<P>
Before his leave, the Chinese minister visited Headquarters
Australian Theater in Sydney Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, the first by a Chinese defense minister to
Australia, the Chinese minister held talks with Australian Prime
Minister John Howard, Foreign Minister Alexander Downer, and
Australian military leaders, including Defense Minister Ian
McLachlan, Australian Defense Force Chief John Baker, on separate
occasions.
</P>
<P>
In his meeting with Chi on Wednesday, Prime Minister Howard
told the defense minister that the Australian government is
pleased to see that relations between the two countries maintain
momentum of sound development in recent years with frequent
exchange of visits by leaders of both nations.
</P>
<P>
Howard said the tour by General Chi to Australia marked an
important progress in the relations between the two militaries.
</P>
<P>
Chi, also deputy chairman of the Central Military Commission of
the People's Republic of China and state councilor, exchanged
views with his Australian counterpart McLachlan on Wednesday on
situation in the Asia-Pacific region and reached consensus on
future exchanges between the two militaries.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Defense Department quoted McLachlan as saying in
a statement the visit raised the defense relationship between the
two countries to a new level.
</P>
<P>
The statement, which was obtained by Xinhua Thursday and is
expected to be released soon, said McLachlan had accepted an
invitation to visit China as soon as practicable.
</P>
<P>
It also said Australian Army Chief General John Sanderson will
visit China later this year.
</P>
<P>
The visit to Australia followed his tour of Japan, Fiji and New
Zealand. 
</P>
