<HEADLINE> Italy Urges U.N. Role in Resolving Iraqi Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The solution to the Iraqi crisis
should be sought through the direct involvement of the United
Nations, Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, Prodi
expressed the Italian government's hopes that Annan's visit to
Baghdad on Friday would be successful.
</P>
<P>
"Since the start of the crisis, which came about because of
Iraq's failure to respect the pertinent resolutions of the United
Nations, the Italian government has been convinced that the
solution should be sought through the direct involvement of the
United Nations and its personnel," he said.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said he expressed this conviction in a joint declaration
with Russian President Boris Yeltsin on February 10.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed his satisfaction over Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak's similar attitude, and over Annan's appreciation
for Italy's stance on the Iraq crisis. 
</P>
