<HEADLINE> Prodi Sees Annan's Bid Decisive For Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano
Prodi said Wednesday that putting the Iraqi crisis in the hands of
the United Nations was a decisive step for safeguarding peace.
</P>
<P>
Referring to a U.N. Security Council mandate for Secretary
General Kofi Annan to pursue a diplomatic approach, Prodi
said: "Moving this controversy to the United Nations is decisive
for safeguarding peace and closely examing the problems."
</P>
<P>
He recalled the joint appeal made with Russian President Boris
Yeltsin for a diplomatic solution little more than a week ago.
</P>
<P>
"When with Yeltsin, I said there could be a solution to the
Iraqi crisis only through the U.N. and a visit by Kofi Annan to
Baghdad," the prime minister added.
</P>
<P>
"Kofi Annan is now leaving," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Though it was clear the problem of U.N. inspections of
suspected weapons sites in Iraq had not been settled, putting the
controversy in the U.N. hands was decisive for protecting the
peace, Prodi said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
