<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S'pore Trying to Join with US to Develop Fighter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Singapore is trying to enter
a joint project with the United States to develop the next
generation of multi-role strike fighter aircraft, the Straits
Times reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It said that Singapore is poised to become the first Asian
country to join the United States in a program to develop the
fighter plane.
</P>
<P>
"A memorandum of understanding (MOU) is under discussion which
could pave the way for the Republic's Ministry of Defense to join
the Joint Strike Fighter (JSF) program as an 'informed customer',"
the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
"The arrangement is another indication of the close
relationship between the governments of the two countries and the
good defense ties they have been cultivating," it commented.
</P>
<P>
The JSF program is said to be aimed at developing and fielding
an affordable family of next-generation multi-role strike fighter
aircraft for the U.S. Navy, Air Force, Marine Corps and its
allies.
</P>
<P>
As an informed customer, the Republic of Singapore Air Force
(RSAF) would be given access to 90 percent of the data on the
program, thus allowing the RSAF to evaluate the JSF against future
requirements.
</P>
<P>
But, Singapore's observer status would not give it key
information on radar-evading stealth technology or allow it to
influence the fighter's design, the paper said, quoting a report
from the weekly aerospace news magazine Flight International.
</P>
<P>
Denmark, the Netherlands and Norway have already become
informed customers, while Italy is holding talks on joining the
program and Australia has been briefed on it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
