<HEADLINE> European Commission Grants Aid to Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, February 19 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission (EC)
has granted an aid package of 26.52 million Rupees (427,742 U.S.
dollars) to Sri Lanka to help the country maintain a sustainable
supply of fuelwood, a government newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Daily News quoted a spokeswoman for the EC in Colombo as
saying the grant has been approved by the EC after the Science and
Technology Ministry of Sri Lanka presented a project proposal last
year.
</P>
<P>
She said the Natural Resource Institute of the United Kingdom
will send an expert team shortly to Sri Lanka to work on the
proposed project, which would last for five years.
</P>
<P>
Due to the absence of indigenous fossil fuel resources, Sri
Lanka is heavily dependent on fuelwood for industrial and
household needs.
</P>
<P>
The spokeswoman said the project was aimed at increasing the
sustainable supply of fuelwood to meet the needs of industrial and
household consumption.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Forestry and Environment Ministry in its Action
Plan 98' said 260 hectares of land will be allocated to plant
trees this year. The move is a major step of the ministry to meet
the timber and fuelwood requirement and to conserve
environmentally vulnerable areas. 
</P>
