<HEADLINE> ASEAN to Restart Progress on Industrial Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Member countries of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) will try to restart
progress on the region's industrial cooperation scheme, the
Bangkok Post reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Thai industry ministry sources as saying
that officials will review the situation in each member country
after the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Progress had been delayed by budget constraints affecting
member nations.
</P>
<P>
Under the industrial cooperation scheme, approved manufacturers
based in any ASEAN member, and with 30 percent local ownership,
will be eligible for preferential tariffs below five percent on
intra-ASEAN trade of parts and components.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that a working group will meet in Bangkok on
February 26 and 27 to discuss ways to speed up tariff cuts.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will find out if there was any concern among
members about slashing tariffs while trying to balance national
budgets, the sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
