<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Foreign Exchange Reserves decreases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's foreign exchange
reserves have decreased to 17.07 billion U.S. dollars as of
February 16 from 20.39 billion dollars recorded on January 15,
Bank Indonesia (BI), the central bank said.
</P>
<P>
A statement signed Wednesday by BI Director Miranda S. Goeltom
said the current level of reserves was enough to finance non-oil
and non-gas imports for 4.2 months.
</P>
<P>
However, the reserves have plunged 41 percent from the record
high of 28.85 set at the end of June last year.
</P>
<P>
The statement said Indonesia still had 1.87 billion dollars in
stand-by loans, which could be cashed anytime the government
needed.
</P>
<P>
The statement did not explain why the reserves were being
depleted.
</P>
<P>
Currency dealers have said the central bank has been active
lately defending the rupiah (national currency) from continuous
attack by intervening both in the spot and swap markets.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has been under speculative attack since the
devaluation of the Thai baht on July 2. Since then the rupiah has
lost more than 70 percent of its value against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
