<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sets Up Nationwide State Property Administration System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, February 19 (Xinhua) -- China's state property
administration system, which was set up a decade ago, has had a
positive impact on the reform of China's economic structure.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhang Youcai, director of Chinese State
Administration of State Property, China's state property is
administrated by people's governments at different levels and
managed by state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
To date, state property administration bodies have been set up
in 94 percent of China's counties, involving a staff of more than
20,000 specialized in evaluating, registering and checking
state-owned property.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, China's total state-owned assets were worth
6.5 trillion yuan with 4.99 trillion yuan of productive property.
</P>
<P>
The present system has guaranteed a clear separation of
property ownership and the operation rights of a state-owned
enterprise which has greatly improved the operation efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Under the former state planning economic system, the operation
and debts of state-owned enterprises used to be controlled by the
central government or local governments at different levels. No
specialized government agencies administered these assets before
1988. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungary, Poland, Czech Issue Communique on NATO Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Hungary, Poland and the Czech
Republic issued a joint communique on Wednesday urging the NATO
countries to formally ratify their membership.
</P>
<P>
The three nations, which were admitted in the first wave of
NATO's expansion, said they hoped to get a rapid and smooth
ratification from the entire 15 NATO members for formal membership
in 1999, the 50th anniversary of the western military bloc.
</P>
<P>
The document was issued after a meeting of the chairmen of the
three countries' parliamentary committees for defense and foreign
affairs.
</P>
<P>
The communique also said a strong and international action,
including the threat of military force, should be made to make
Iraq comply with U.N. resolutions on weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
The three parliaments would also improve cooperation on issues
of regional and world security.
</P>
<P>
Only when they achieved strength and security in central Europe
could they establish a peaceful and cooperative relationship with
Russia and Ukraine, the document said.
</P>
<P>
The three countries called on NATO to accept other European
countries which are able to meet the conditions for membership and
voiced support for Slovenia, Romania and the Baltic countries to
be admitted at a proper time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
