<HEADLINE> Gas Pipeline Will Change Central American Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The building of a gas
pipeline between Mexico and Guatemala will pave the way to change
the economic structures of countries in the region, the Guatemala
Minister of Energy and Mining Leonel Lopez says.
</P>
<P>
Lopez said the project will change the economy of countries in
Central America and extend electrical coverage.
</P>
<P>
The 710-kilometer line will run from Pemex city, southeast of
Mexico, to the northern border of Guatemala through Honduras,
Nicaragua, El Salvador, Costa Rica and Panama.
</P>
<P>
The objectives are to transport natural gas to Costa Rica and
Panama, with an initial capacity of 830 million cubic meters a
year, rising to 8.94 billion cubic meters in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Lopez said Central America is planning to concentrate
electrical inter-connection over a six year term. Natural gas will
help reduce the demand on electrical energy and and meet growing
domestic and industrial energy demands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
