<HEADLINE> Brazil Invests More in Fruit Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The Brazilian government will
invest 1.5 billion U.S. dollars in increasing fruit production and
promoting fruit exports, in an aim to become the world's top fruit
exporter in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian Agriculture Ministry says fruit exports
(including dried and candied fruits) reached 1.88 million tons in
1997, an increase of 7.4 percent over last year. The exports
earned more than 1.69 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Brazil has more than two million hectares growing fruit, with
an annual production of more than 31 million tons. This includes
orange, avocado and papaya which are in first places in the world.
</P>
<P>
Orange juice, the biggest export product of Brazil, amounted to
1.18 million tons, worth more than one billion dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
To occupy international markets, the Brazilian government began
to implement a "support plan" for the development of fruit growing
in the northeast last September. It predicts the cultivation of a
million hectares in a few years and the annual creation of 200,000
jobs.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, the authorities would invest 1.5 billion
dollars in 10 years to increase the plantation areas.
</P>
<P>
The main markets for Brazilian fruit exports are the European
Union countries, the United States and the Southern Common Market
countries, and there are plans to broaden exports to Japan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
