<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Revenue Department Tax Collections Reach Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 19 (Xinhua) -- The Thai revenue department
tax collections in January amounted to 47 billion baht (about 1
billion U.S. dollars), 1.1 percent more than the month's target,
according to Phaithoon Pongkesorn, A spokeswoman for the
department.
</P>
<P>
She was quoted Thursday by the Bangkok Post as saying that the
department succeeded in collection corporate, petroleum, sales and
special taxes last month. However, the department did not receive
much in the way of personal taxes as workers have been hard hit by
the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Although the department received more taxes last month, the
department could not meet the revenue target in the first four
months of fiscal 1998, October 1997 to January 1998.
</P>
<P>
The department collected a total of 162 billion (about 3.4
billion dollars) in tax the first four months of the fiscal year.
However, that fell short of the target by 1.79 billion baht (about
38 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The department's income target for fiscal 1998 is 541 billion
baht (about 11.5 billion dollars). The total revenue target for
the Thai government is 872 billion baht (about 18.5 billion
dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
