<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Trade Deficit Declines in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's trade deficit in
1997 has dropped by 195 million U.S. dollars due to the impressive
performance in exports and a decline in consumer goods imports,
the Central Bank said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The deficit during the January-November period in 1997 was
1,077 million dollars, compared with 1,272 million dollars in the
corresponding period a previous year.
</P>
<P>
The bank attributed the drop to the prudent economic management
of the government and the incentives offered to the export based
industries by the government.
</P>
<P>
The total exports grew by 14.4 percent during the first 11
months last year, while imports rose only by 6.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
During the period, export earnings amounted to 182 billion
Rupees (2.94 billion dollars), a 23.7 percent increase over 1996.
</P>
<P>
The investment goods and intermediary goods imports have
increased to 70 billion Rupees (1.13 billion dollars) during
January and November, which industrial experts say will help
strengthen the local industrial sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
