<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Set Up Sino-foreign Tourism Agency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 19 (Xinhua) -- China will launch Sino-foreign
joint venture travel agencies on a trial basis this year in a move
to expand facilities for travelers and offset losses caused by the
Southeast Asian financial crisis, China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The English newspaper quoted He Guangwei, Chairman of the
National Tourism Administration, as saying that this is part of
the administration's multi-pronged effort to make sure the tourism
industry maintains a relatively high growth rate this year,
although the industry is already feeling the effects of the
financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Other measures include sponsoring more tourism promotion
activities and fairs in Japan, Europe and the United States,
sending 10 promotion delegations overseas and developing the
domestic tourism market.
</P>
<P>
New markets will be developed in India and Russia, where
well-off people have the money to travel abroad.
</P>
<P>
He admitted the financial crisis will produce some impact on
the industry this year because countries in Southeast Asia are
major markets for China's tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Many tourists from these countries are expected to cancel their
travel plans due to local currency depreciation and shrinking
domestic expenditure.
</P>
<P>
Worse still, the cheaper currencies in countries such as
Thailand, Indonesia and South Korea will lure away some of Western
tourists originally destined for China.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the tourism industry will never give up the
Southeast Asian market and will develop more suitable tourism
products to attract travellers from these countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
