<HEADLINE> Thailand to Repatriate Students in Baghdad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 19 (Xinhua) -- The Thai embassy in Iraq has
suggested the repatriation of 23 Thai students now in Baghdad
following reports the united states is expected to launch a strike
between February 25-28, according to a Thai foreign ministry
source.
</P>
<P>
The source was quoted Thursday by the Bangkok Post as saying
that the embassy sought advice from the ministry, and cautioned
that a late departure from Baghdad might face congestion at the
nearest border pass, with possible shortages of food, petrol, and
shelter.
</P>
<P>
An earlier report said the embassy had prepared an evacuation
plan that provided for travel by car from Baghdad to Amman,
Jordan. besides the students, 20 other Thais are living in Iraq,
including 14 embassy officials and employees.
</P>
<P>
According to the embassy, Malaysia had already sent back 62
students. the Philippines and Indonesia planned to send back their
women and children by February 21 and 25, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria, turkey, Poland and Russia had also begun moving their
people out of Baghdad, the embassy said. 
</P>
