<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Clinton Legal Defense Fund Set Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 18 (Xinhua) -- With U.S. President Bill
Clinton owing more than 3.2 million dollars in legal bills, former
Senator David Pryor of Arkansas Wednesday announced the creation
of a new legal defense fund.
</P>
<P>
It will replace the fund shut down in December after it failed
to generate sufficient contributions.
</P>
<P>
The legal bills are mounting for Clinton, with a multitude of
litigation underway.
</P>
<P>
The trustees of the new fund can solicit contributions because
Clinton is not officially involved in the trust. The previous fund
could only accept contributions that donors "passively" offered.
</P>
<P>
The fund will solicit contributions of up to 10,000 dollars, a
major increase on 1,000 dollar limit of the previous fund.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference announcing the new fund, Pryor said,"I am
deeply concerned about the personal burden placed on the president
by the enormous and ever-mounting legal expenses that they have
incurred."
</P>
<P>
Both the White House counsel's office and the Office of
Government Ethics gave the new trust fund the green light to
solicit funds to help pay the Clintons' legal bills.
</P>
<P>
It will not take contributions from government employees,
corporations, labor unions, political action committees or their
registered lobbyists and will disclose its activities twice a
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
