<HEADLINE> Brazil's Trade Deficit Reaches 660 Million Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Brazil registered a trade
deficit of 660 million U.S. dollars in January, far less than that
of the previous five months.
</P>
<P>
Mauricio Cortes, the minister of Exterior Commerce, on
Wednesday attributed the lower deficit to rising exports and
dwindling imports.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's January export was 3.9 billion dollars, an increase of
11.5 percent that that of the previous month, and import stood at
4.56 billion dollars, down by 12.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
While the European Union bought more than 1 billion dollars of
Brazilian products in January, exports to South Korea, Malaysia,
the Philippines, Thailand and Indonesia dropped a dramatic 38
percent to 59 million dollars due to the financial crisis in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Brazil registered a trade deficit of 8.37 billion
dollars with exports totaling 52.986 billion dollars and imports
at 61.358 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
