<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Container Transport Up in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 19 (Xinhua) -- China handled more than 10
million TEUs (Twenty-foot Equivalent Units) in 1997, up 24 percent
over the previous year, China Trade News has reported.
</P>
<P>
The figure excluded containers through Hong Kong and the volume
handled by motor vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai Port transported 2.52 million TEUs last year, ranking
first in China and 12th in the world.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen, a special economic zone in south China, came in
second in the country with 1.15 million TEUs last year.
</P>
<P>
The container-handling volume of Qingdao Port in east China's
Shandong Province exceeded 1 million TEUs, ranking third in the
country.
</P>
<P>
China's container transport industry experienced an average
annual growth of 25 percent in the last decade, three times the
world average, said Song Dexing, chief of the container transport
section under the Ministry of Communications.
</P>
<P>
In the 1992-97 period, 40 overseas companies cooperated with
their Chinese partners to build container relay centers. Twenty of
the top container companies in the world have opened container
routes in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
