<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak PM Calls for Development of Hydro-Power Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif said Wednesday that besides efforts to develop coal
fields for power generation, the government was trying to sort out
problems related to the development of major hydro-power projects.
</P>
<P>
It would enable Pakistan to utilize significant sources of
surface water available in the country, said Sharif while
addressing the concluding session of the two-day Oil and Gas
Summit.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said his government was trying to develop the most
optimum energy mix customized to domestic conditions and
peculiarities.
</P>
<P>
"We wish to achieve the dual socio-economic objective of
ensuring availability of energy at affordable price while
promoting investment in the development of the energy thus
creating more employment opportunities,' he said.
</P>
<P>
Sharif stressed for preparing a long-term fuel energy strategy
to support a sustained growth of economy at about seven percent
per annum as it was essential that future strategies were
formulated by integrating both short-term and long-term measures.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the need for fast developing the national
economy, saying that national focus on infrastructural development
projects would enable Pakistan to play its central role in linking
various regional business blocks and exploit regional markets,
specially for energy supplies.
</P>
<P>
He said the government was keen to substitute imported oil with
imported piped gas from the neighboring countries to meet its
energy requirements.
</P>
<P>
Sharif also said that his government was determined to cut down
expenditure on uneconomical ventures and encourage private
investment in energy projects.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister asked the experts participating in the oil
and gas summit to look closely at the opportunities that have been
offered for profitable investment especially in the energy supply
and infrastructure sector.
</P>
<P>
He urged them to "join us in our endeavors to vitalize national
economy through profitable and mutually-beneficial economic
cooperation and investment".
</P>
<P>
Pakistan' energy supply and demand figures are dominated by oil
and gas which have become critical to the economy. Pakistan has to
spend about 2.5 billion U.S. dollars annually on oil imports.
</P>
<P>
Sharif called for better planning and management to reduce
heavy oil imports through optimum exploration of indigenous
resources.
</P>
<P>
Huge coal deposits have been discovered in the Thar area of
Sindh province and the estimated reserves are about 176 billion
tones while the remaining proven reserves of natural gas in
Pakistan are over 20 trillion cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
Overall theoretical potential is as high as 200 trillion cubic
feet. So far, a total of 600 million barrels of oil reserves have
been proven to exist in the country although the potential is
considered to be much higher.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said the government has, therefore, given liberal
incentives for exploration in large unexplored offshore areas
where major oil and gas fields are expected to be discovered.
</P>
<P>
The two-day Oil and Gas Summit was attended by about 370
delegates from 26 countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0342 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwanese Given 15-Year Sentence in The Mainland for Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Ruan Weiming, a Taiwanese who
does business in Shanghai, was recently sentenced to 15 years in
prison for a 510,000-yuan (61,000 US dollars) fraud case involving
IDD fees.
</P>
<P>
He was also deprived of political rights for four years by the
No. 1 Intermediate People's Court of Shanghai Municipality.
</P>
<P>
Ruan, 43, rented offices and IDD telephones from nine Shanghai
companies from 1995 on for his telecommunications company
Jiexin. He then had employees install a hi-tech automatic
telephone exchange on the rented telephone line.
</P>
<P>
The company then offered prices that were 25 percent off the
standard telephone rates of the post and telecommunications
department for IDD calls, and got a large number of customers. To
avoid trouble with the police, his employees ran away after the
telephone fees were paid.
</P>
<P>
Since October of 1995, the nine companies that signed rental
contracts with Ruan have suffered a loss of 510,000 yuan on IDD
calls.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0343 </DOCNO>
