<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Manufactured Exports Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, February 19 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand exported more
manufactured products in 1997 despite the Asian economic crisis in
the second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
Manufactured exports in the year reached 8 billion NZ dollars
(4.6 billion U.S. dollars), while elaborately transformed exports
hit a new high of 5.6 billion (3.3 billion U.S. dollars), the
Manufacturers Federation President David Moloney was quoted by the
Wellington newspaper "The Dominion" on Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the eight billion dollars accounted for 39 percent of
the total exports and did not include meat, dairy products, fish,
wool or wood pulp.
</P>
<P>
Growth was expected for some months because of the lower NZ
dollar.
</P>
<P>
"But clearly this growth is a result of much more than just the
level of the currency because several leading industry sectors
have kept on growing strongly right through the previous 18
months, when out exchange rate was very high," Moloney said.
</P>
<P>
He listed the sectors producing electronics and electrical
equipment, industry machinery and equipment, transport equipment
and plastic goods as the top performers in export. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
