<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Government Posts Budget Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 19 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government
posted a 1.87 billion pesos (46.75 million U.S. dollars) budget
surplus in January compared to a deficit of 3.18 billion pesos
(79.5 million dollars) in January last year.
</P>
<P>
Documents from the Bureau of Treasury showed Thursday that
improved revenue collections amounting to 44.19 billion pesos (1.1
billion dollars) during the period boosted the government's fiscal
position.
</P>
<P>
The revenue collected last month were substantially higher than
the 37.44 billion pesos (936 million dollars) collections during
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The government's two main revenue-yielding agencies, the Bureau
of Revenue and Bureau of Customs, which had incurred huge
shortfalls last year, both exceeded their collection targets for
the month.
</P>
<P>
Fiscal officials said that if these positive developments
continued, the government could perform much better than the
modest 1 billion pesos (25 million dollars) surplus targeted for
this year.
</P>
<P>
The government was originally hoping for a 16 billion pesos
(400 million dollars) surplus this year, but this was scaled down
in consideration of the adverse impact of the currency crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
