<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guang'an Achievements Commemorate Deng Xiaoping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, February 19 (Xinhua) -- Rapid economic growth, the
large number of people who escaped poverty and the construction of
30 roads over the past year represent monumental achievements the
people of Guang'an feel appropriately commemorate the 1st
anniversary of Deng Xiaoping's death on February 19, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Guang'an County, in southwest China's Sichuan Province, was the
birthplace of Deng Xiaoping, chief architect of China's reform and
opening drive.
</P>
<P>
Local people heeded Deng's call for "building a better
Guang'an" by launching a road construction campaign in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Construction of an expressway linking Guang'an with Chongqing
Municipality is in full swing, with over 2,500 meters of a
4,775-meter Huaying Mountain highway tunnel, China's longest,
already completed.
</P>
<P>
Work continued nonstop on the eve of Lunar New Year, the major
traditional Chinese festival which commenced on January 28.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that about one million people are working on
related projects.
</P>
<P>
Guang'an has also engaged in arduous efforts to help more local
residents escape poverty.
</P>
<P>
Guang'an, a major agricultural area, initiated its poverty
eradication program by building houses for over 2,500 rural
families who formerly lacked housing or lived in cave dwellings.
</P>
<P>
Statistics for 1997 show that the county's industrial output
value jumped by 18 percent, ranking the second of the province;
the total retail sales by 20 percent, ranking the third; and
financial revenue by 21.3 percent, ranking the fourth.
</P>
<P>
The fact that people refer to Guang'an as the "Hometown of Deng
Xiaoping, one of the greatest men of the century" has brought fame
and wealth to the county.
</P>
<P>
A record 700,000 domestic and overseas tourists visited Deng's
former home during 1997.
</P>
<P>
A number of Guang'an natives have left the county to study
advanced experiences in economically developed areas across the
nation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
