<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Lewinsky Case Coverage Confuses Reporting with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Opinion and speculation
have routinely been mingled with reporting in coverage of the
allegations that U.S. President Bill Clinton had a relationship
with a former White House intern, according to a study by a group
of journalists.
</P>
<P>
The study, released Wednesday by the Committee of Concerned
Journalist, suggested a decline in journalistic standards,
particularly a growing emphasis on disseminating the latest
developments in a competitive story rather than determining their
accuracy.
</P>
<P>
"The media culture today is oriented around talking about the
news rather than reporting it," said Tom Rosenstiel, a media
critic and vice chairman of the committee.
</P>
<P>
The study was billed as "a snapshot of the news media culture"
in the first week after Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel,
expanded his investigation to determine whether Clinton obstructed
justice or lied under oath regarding his relationship with former
intern Monica Lewinsky. Clinton has denied any improper
relationship.
</P>
<P>
The study looked at the news coverage of various forms to
determine the extent to which they relied on unnamed sources or
other media to deliver the story. It also tried to quantify the
amount of each account that was fact-based rather than
speculation.
</P>
<P>
The examination conducted for the committee by Princeton Survey
Research Associates found that 41 percent of the reporting was
either analysis, opinion or speculation. Forty percent of the
reporting based on anonymous sourcing relied on a single source,
while only one statement in 100 was based on two or more named
sources.
</P>
<P>
The number of people who have firsthand knowledge of the
Lewinsky case is quite small, and the number of reporters with
direct access to them isn't too much bigger. The study found that
organizations with better sources relied less on analysis and
opinion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
