<HEADLINE> Hundreds Protest in London Against Military Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of people gathered in
the Whitehall street opposite Downing Street in Central London
Wednesday evening to protest against possible air strike on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators urged the British government to give up its
plan to bomb Iraq because only the innocent people could suffer
from the military action.
</P>
<P>
"No Blood for Oil!", "Don't Bomb Iraq!", "Save the innocent
people!" the people chanted.
</P>
<P>
"We hold no brief for (Iraqi President) Saddam Hussein. But we
demand that the Labor government back off from this unjustified
war, which will only kill the Iraqi people," one speaker told the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
Britain's House of Commons gave overwhelming support on Tuesday
to the government's hard line on Iraq, backing its readiness to
use force against President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
During the protest, two women and a man were arrested as they
tried to handcuff themselves to the gates of Downing Street, where
Prime Minister Tony Blair's office is located. But the
demonstration held on the other side of Whitehall continued
without disruption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
