<HEADLINE> N.Irish Talks Break, Sinn Fein Bid for Talks Adjourned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The Northern Irish peace talks,
currently held in Dublin, Ireland Republic, broke up on Wednesday
with no decision on Sinn Fein's fate in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
British Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam said the British
and Irish governments had not decided yet whether to expel IRA's
political wing Sinn Fein for IRA's involvement in two killings in
Belfast last week.
</P>
<P>
"We have been going for three days listening to Sinn Fein's
presentation of their case and the views of the other parties.
</P>
<P>
"The governments will now take into account the points made by
Sinn Fein and the other parties in making our final
determination," Mowlam said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The Northern Ireland peace talks are due to reopen in Belfast,
capital of the divided British province, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the legal bid by Sinn Fein to stay in the peace
talks was adjourned until tomorrow, according to local reports.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein, which denied any involvement in the bloody violence,
sought legal action on Tuesday to block the expulsion of the party
from the multi-party peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The threat of expulsion from the talks hangs over Sinn Fein
after police claimed the IRA was involved in two recent murders.
</P>
</TEXT>
