<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-18 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Expects U.S. to Lift Arms Ban Soon: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 18 (Xinhua) -- It was a question of time
before the United States lifted its arms trade embargo against South
Africa, Deputy President Thabo Mbeki's office said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has done everything possible to assure the U.S. of its
commitment to complying with the terms set out in an agreement reached
between the two countries last year, South African Press Association
quoted Mbeki's legal advisor, Mojanku Gumbi, as saying in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
The embargo was imposed in the 1980s to prevent South Africa from
selling technology imported from the U.S. to other countries.
</P>
<P>
The issue will be discussed by Mbeki and his U.S. counterpart, Al
Gore, when the two men meet next week, Gumbi told a news conference on
the U.S.-South African Binational Commission meeting.
</P>
<P>
But she said the issue would not be on the agenda of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, international news agencies reported that the
U.S. had refused to let Sweden export its JAS 39 Gripen jet fighter to
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The jet is manufactured by a consortium led by the Swedish company,
Saab, and its partner British Aerospace. A third of its components are
from the U.S.
</P>
<P>
The consortium hopes to contribute about 40 aircraft to South
Africa's military modernization program, and has offered counter-trade
deals to the value of 3.75 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is trying to re-equip its National Defense Force by
buying military equipment worth 12 billion Rand (2.4 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Six countries -- Britain, Canada, France, Germany, Italy and Spain
-- had reportedly been shortlisted by the South African Defense
Department as potential weapon suppliers.
</P>
<P>
Frank Chikane, Director-General of Mbeki's office, told the
news conference that there was no tension between South Africa and the
U.S. on the arms trade.
</P>
<P>
Washington was mad at Pretoria when the latter said it would sell
military equipment to Syria in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
