<HEADLINE> UK Rules out New Investigation into 89 Soccer Tragedy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 18 (Xinhua) -- A British minister said on
Wednesday there would be no fresh inquiry into the 1989
Hillsborough football stadium tragedy.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Jack Straw told parliament there was no
"significant new evidence" to justify a new inquiry into the
Hillsborough football match incident.
</P>
<P>
For that reason, there were no grounds to quash its verdict of
accidental death, he added.
</P>
<P>
The tragedy at the ground of Sheffield Wednesday in northern
England occurred ahead of a cup semi-final match between
Nottingham Forest and Liverpool.
</P>
<P>
Ninety-six Liverpool supporters died after they crushed each
other when they found themselves unable to leave an overcrowded
section of the stands because gates were locked.
</P>
<P>
The families of the victims, who have long complained that no
one has ever stood trial for their part in the tragedy, called
Straw to step down.
</P>
<P>
"We are disgusted with the report....The public will feel as
appalled as we do," spokesman Trevor Hicks told a news conference

