<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Economic Growth Loses Momentum Late 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Germany's economic upturn lost
momentum in the final quarter of 1997 with industrial output
growing only by a seasonally-adjusted 0.5 percent, the German
central bank said today.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest economic report issued by the central
bank, the Bundesbank, on Wednesday, the German industry also saw a
2.5 percent drop in foreign orders in the last quarter of 1997
compared with the previous quarter. The booming export demand has
been the only major driving force for the country's economic
growth so far.
</P>
<P>
Although the Bundesbank said that it was still too early to
estimate the full impact of the financial crisis in Asia on the
German economy, it had at least made a considerable dent in
Germany's economic confidence.
</P>
<P>
For some German industrial sectors, serious problems could
arise from the combination of weaker demand and stronger
competition from Asia due to the financial crisis, the Bundesbank
said.
</P>
<P>
While urging the trade unions to continue to pursue a policy of
moderate wage growth, the central bank today also repeated its
call on politicians to push ahead the stalled structural reforms
in a bid to boost the country's competitiveness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980219.0414 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Extending Medical Insurance for Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 18 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Wednesday ordered federal agencies to seek out millions of
children who are eligible for Medicaid but not enrolled.
</P>
<P>
"Nothing can weigh more heavily on your mind than the health of
your child," Clinton said Wednesday during a visit to Children's
National Medical Center here.
</P>
<P>
Clinton asked eight agencies to make a concerted effort to
enroll three million uninsured children in Medicaid -- the federal
health insurance program covering poor, elderly and disabled
Americans.
</P>
<P>
The agencies are the Social Security Administration and the
departments of Agriculture, Interior, Education, Health and Human
Services, Housing and Urban Development, Labor and Treasury.
</P>
<P>
Extending coverage to Medicaid-eligible children, Clinton said,
would go a long way toward insuring five million children within
five years under the 24 billion-dollar Children's Health Insurance
Program.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's fiscal 1999 budget plan includes 900 million dollar
over five years for outreach on children's health, including using
schools and child care centers to enroll Medicaid-eligible
children. States would have the option of automatically enrolling
children in Medicaid before completing all of the eligibility and
enrollment forms.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that two states, Colorado and South Carolina, have
joined Alabama in expanding their state child health coverage
under the children's program.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Clinton said, 14 states have submitted expansion
plans to the Department of Health and Human Services, and 30
states are coming up with plans to address coverage for uninsured
children.
</P>
<P>
"I still have a hard time believing that this country, with the
finest health care system in the world, cannot figure out how to
give affordable, quality health insurance coverage to every single
child in America," Clinton said. "This is wrong. If we really
want to make America strong for the 21st century, we will correct
it."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
