<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Top Aides met with Opposition to Military Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The Clinton
administration's foreign policy team Wednesday held a forum at
Ohio State University, Columbus, Ohio, in effort to make the
case for U.S. military action against Iraq, but were met with
loud oppositions from the audience.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, Defense Secretary
William Cohen and National Security Adviser Sandy Berger, who
made the team for the marketing campaign, made their remarks
over jeers from the audience, trying their best to convince the
people of the necessity of military action to force Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein to comply with U.N. resolution on
weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
But right after their statements, the audience sharply
challenged the U.S. authority to launch an attack on Iraq, given
a lack of support from Iraq's neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Some of the protesters held aloft a banner that said: "No
War." And some shouted "No war, no war," "One, two, three, four,
we don't want your racist war."
</P>
<P>
A person identified as an assistant professor at Ohio State
University asked the three top aides of the Clinton
administration whether the United States has "the moral right"
to attack Iraq.
</P>
<P>
And another questioner said as many as 100,000 Iraqi
civilians could be killed by U.S. air strikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Ohio State University forum was one of several places
that the Clinton administration is trying to drum up support
from the public.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton said on Tuesday that "the American
people have to be ready" for the looming military action.
</P>
<P>
Albright will continue her trip, first to Tennessee State
University in Nashville and then to the University of South
Carolina at Columbia, where she will continue to try to do
mobilization campaign for the military action against Iraq.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
