<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi FM Again in Amman for Consultations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed
Saeed al-Sahhaf arrived here Wednesday, the second time in three
days, for further consultations with Jordanian officials on the
Iraqi-U.N. crisis over weapons inspection.
</P>
<P>
This was the continuation of his multi-nation tour, which has
taken him to Syria, Egypt, Jordan, Lebanon, France and Iran, to
explain Iraq's position and solicit support for a political
solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi position was based on reaching a balanced diplomatic
solution that could satisfy the demands of all the concerned
parties and avoid a military strike by the United States, the
foreign minister said in a statement upon his arrival.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, al-Sahhaf said that Iraq very much
appreciated Jordan`s stand about the crisis as well as its
efforts to help avert military strikes.
</P>
<P>
He added that Iranian leaders also affirmed to him Iran`s
opposition to any military action, with which the U.S. wanted to
compel Iraq to open all the sites to inspections without any
preconditions.
</P>
<P>
The minister did not elaborate on what results his tour had
achieved so far.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Deputy Prime Minister for Development Affairs and
Minister of Foreign Affairs Jawad Anani greeted al-Sahhaf at the
Amman Ali International Airport.
</P>
<P>
Anani told reporters that Jordan's efforts focused on sparing
Iraq the dangerous consequences of military actions and there was
possibility of reaching a diplomatic solution that could meet the
demands of all the concerned sides.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahhaf once was in Amman from February 12 to 16. He met with
senior Jordanian officials and expressed willingness to hold
direct political talk with the U.S. to end the crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
