<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Relations With US Aid Agency: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The relationship between
South Africa and the United States Agency for International
Development (USAid) would be reviewed following reports that the
agency meddled in South Africa's internal affairs, Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki's office announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The priorities of USAid funding might have to change, South
African Press Association quoted director-general in Mbeki's
office, Frank Chikane, as saying in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
All aid should be aimed at assisting South Africa to achieve
its objective of transforming the society, Chikane told a news
conference on the upcoming U.S.-South African Binational
Commission meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Saturday Star newspaper said last week that a U.S.
Congress report accused the USAid of directing its funds mainly
to conferences and other policy-formulating activities, rather
than poverty relief in the country.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Lester Munster, a member of the U.S. House of
Representatives' Foreign Relations Committee, as saying that the
USAid used its fund to play a major role in key South African
political issues, including race and affirmative action policies,
land, education, labor and healthcare policies.
</P>
<P>
Munster said the USAid interfered in South African domestic
policy to the point of making the Mandela government's work more
difficult.
</P>
<P>
Chikane said the South African Department of Foreign Affairs
had compiled a report on the relationship between USAid and South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
The report was discussed with the United States and USAid
officials, who agreed that a review was needed.
</P>
<P>
Chikane said the issue would not be discussed at next week's
Binational Commission meeting, which is to be attended by U.S.
Vice- President Al Gore. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
