<HEADLINE> U.S. Air Force B-1B Bomber Crashes in Kentucky </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 18 (Xinhua) -- A B-1B bomber of the United
States Air Force crashed in western Kentucky Wednesday and
exploded. But all four crew members survived.
</P>
<P>
The B-1B bomber was flying out of Dyess Air Force Base near
Abilene, Texas and was on a routine training mission when it
crashed, officials at the Air Force Base in Virginia was quoted by
the Associated Press as saying.
</P>
<P>
Police said that all the four people aboard the bomber were
found alive after the crash in a rural area near Marion, west of
Kentucky, but their conditions were not immediately known.
</P>
<P>
Air Force officials said that the bomber was not one of the
additional warplanes being dispatched to the Persian Gulf. There
was no immediate information about the cause of the crash.
</P>
<P>
It was the second crash of the 200 million U.S. dollar bomber
in five months. Last September, a B-1B crashed in a training
mission on the Montana prairie, killing all four people aboard.
</P>
<P>
The B-1B "Lancer" bomber is one of three long-range heavy
bombers in the Air Force arsenal, in addition to the B-2 Stealth
bomber and the venerable B-52. The B-1B can fly intercontinental
bombing missions without refueling.
</P>
<P>
The bomber was designed in the 1970s as a nuclear bomb-dropper
and it has been converted since then for conventional missions.
The bomber is being deployed to the Mideast for the first time in
a potential combat role. 
</P>
</TEXT>
