<HEADLINE> Turkey Calls for Positive Greek Response to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Despite an earlier rejection
from Greece, Turkey called on the neighbor on Wednesday to respond
positively to a peace initiative, the Anatolia News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is expecting an "official and serious" response from the
Greek government to the initiative concerning issues of the Aegean
Sea, Turkish Foreign Ministry spokesman Necati Utkan told a news
briefing.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that our proposal will be considered (by Greece) and
that the answer will be a positive one," Utkan said.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem presented a verbal note
Last Thursday to the Greek ambassador in Ankara, proposing to find
a peaceful settlement for the issues of the Aegean Sea.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that the foreign ministries of the two countries
hold talks on ways and means to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
But Greece rejected the proposal on Monday, saying that it does
not think that the issue should be solved through bilateral talks.
</P>
<P>
"The comprehensive political talks on the bilateral problems
that Turkey has proposed could never and will never take place, "
Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece, both members of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization, have long been at odds over the Aegean issues,
including the airspace limits, sea-bed resources and sovereignty
over some islands.
</P>
<P>
Greece maintains that the problems should be solved through
international arbitration, while Turkey prefers to seek a solution
through bilateral negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
