<HEADLINE> European Shares Up, London Hits New Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
extended their recent gains and ended higher Wednesday, with
London hitting another record closing high, boosted by a strong
dollar, a firm Wall Street and the buoyant banks sector.
</P>
<P>
Britain's FTSE 100 index of leading shares were underpinned by
a solid bullish tone and the index closed at its second
consecutive record high at 5,723.4, up 13.9 points.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that the market remained well bid despite
Wednesday's strong UK retail sales figures and early profit-taking
on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
UK retail sales were up 1.8 percent last month, and were 6.9
percent higher over the same month last year, the biggest
year-on-year increase since June 1988.
</P>
<P>
Traders said only a real dose of gloom, like a batch of poor
results, would take the momentum out of recent gains.
</P>
<P>
Germany's DAX-30 index ended at 4628.83, up 26.43 points, or
0.57 percent. Automobile shares outperformed the market on
technical factors.
</P>
<P>
French stocks were little changed, having relinquished most
early gains as the market consolidated and digested Tuesday's
strong gains, with the CAC-40 index up 1.26 points at 3,281.71 by
the close of the session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
