<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Normalizes Religious Tolerance Edict 400 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 18 (Xinhua) -- France is marking the 400th
anniversary of a religious tolerance edict, the Edict of Nantes,
which was signed in 1598 by the then French King Henri IV and
recognized the legal status of Christian Protestants to co-exist
with Roman Catholics for the first time in French history.
</P>
<P>
In a speech made Wednesday at the United Nations Educational,
Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO), French President
Jacques Chirac said that the signing of Edict of Nantes is "the
strong moment of awakening of the national conscience" of France.
</P>
<P>
He also praised the edict for ending the religious war in
France and bringing national unity and the spirit of tolerance to
the country.
</P>
<P>
"France was strengthened and knew from this text a period more
secure and more peaceful because the choice of tolerance,
co-existence, not that of hatred and rejection of others, had been
made," said Chirac.
</P>
<P>
He said that some ideas from the edict, such as the recognition
of differences, later led to the establishment of the "essential
values of the French republic" in 1789.
</P>
<P>
However, the Edict of Nantes was abolished in 1685 by King
Louis XIV, 87 years after its signing. The abolition resulted in
severe persecutions of Protestants in France and forced 200,000 of
them to go into exile in Germany and the Netherlands, two European
Protestant nations at that time.
</P>
<P>
"Civil peace is always fragile. The values and principles which
allow people to live together should be reaffirmed and defended
all the time,"said Chirac. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
