<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Adams May be Given Visa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 18 (Xinhua) - The U.S. State Department
said on Wednesday that it was considering a request from Gerry
Adams, leader of Sinn Fein in Northern Island of Britain, for a
visa to visit the United States.
</P>
<P>
"We're considering the application," State Department spokesman
James Foley told a regular news briefing.
</P>
<P>
The head of Sinn Fein, the political arm the Irish Republican
Army (IRA), last visited the United States in September last year.
</P>
<P>
Foley said he did not know what criteria would be used to
decide whether to grant the visa.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the Britain government, accusing the IRA of killing
two men last week in violation of a cease-fire it declared last
July, decided to expel Sinn Fein from multi-party Northern Ireland
peace talks under way in Dublin.
</P>
<P>
The Irish government also said it believed the IRA does have a
case to answer about last week's two murders.
</P>
<P>
However, Sinn Fein says it is totally separate from the IRA and
is committed to a peaceful resolution of the Irish conflict and
began a legal legal battle on Wednesday to stop Britain throwing
it out of the talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
