<HEADLINE> Greece Not to Take Initiative to Improve Ties With Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Greece decided on Wednesday not
to take the initiative in improving its relations with neighboring
Turkey, Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on a meeting presided over by Greek Prime Minister
Costas Simitis concerning developments in Greek-Turkish relations
and the Cyprus issue, Reppas said that it was decided that there
was no margin for undertaking an initiative to better ties with
Ankara.
</P>
<P>
"We consider that presently the conditions for doing something
different from what has been done thus far are not in place," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish side, he stressed, must show its respect for the
rules of good neighborliness and abstain from the increasingly
provocations, violations and infringements in order to create a
favorable climate for fruitful contacts between officials of the
two countries, whose relations are at odds over decades for
territorial waters, airspace rights, the delimitation of
continental shelf in the Aegean Sea and the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
He added that no meeting between Greek Foreign Minister
Theodoros Pangalos and his Turkish counterpart Ismail Cem had been
scheduled, and any such meeting, which was possible and desirable
in the framework of international organizations, had no relation
to dialogue, and with any form of negotiations on Greece's
sovereign rights.
</P>
<P>
As for the Cyprus problem, he said that Greece would contribute
towards an effective tackling of the problem in the framework of
the initiative regarding the expected renewed mediation by
Washington.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed that a lot had to be done still for "a just and
viable solution to emerge." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
