<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IDB Supports Education Technologies in El Salvador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American
Development Bank (IDB) Wednesday announced the approval of a 73.2
million U.S. dollar loan to El Salvador to expand and improve
basic education through the use of new technologies.
</P>
<P>
The resources will be used to help expand coverage of the third
cycle of basic education, grades seven through nine, to reach
24,900 new students, closing 47 percent of the gap that is
expected to be created by a high rate of population growth.
Expanded use of school video libraries will be an important
element in carrying out the phase of the program.
</P>
<P>
For urban and rural schools serving grades one through three in
disadvantaged communities, the resource will be provided to help
expand the use of interactive radio to improving teaching for
570,000 rural children in mathematics and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
A fund will be set up to finance education projects conducted
by school administration organizations so as to promote community
participation in the investments, and learning resource centers
will be introduced into schools to apply new technologies.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the program is some 81.3 million dollars.
Local counterpart funds total 8.1 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
